text:
How much do I like Reading Terminal Market? Let me count the ways:

1. Iovine Brothers Produce - Even at the cheapest of supermarkets, I couldn't get a whole bag of the freshest, highest quality vegetables for $5. Same goes to the nuts and snacks on the southern wall, where else can you buy them in such a state of quality at such prices?

2. Godshall's Poultry - Instead of the yellowed, hormoned chicken you get from the supermarket, these are the freshest, tastiest chicken you can find in the city. And fresh chickens do make a difference in taste. Of course, they do have ducks, quails, turkeys and eggs.

3. Martin's and John Yi's is where I get my meat and seafood, Martin's is always a few bucks cheaper and John Yi captures me with their neon signs.

4. 4 Seasons Juice Bar has the tastiest fruit smoothies and blends around. My favorite is Pineapple (for sweetness) + Banana (for texture) + Orange (for taste). Nothing beats a 20oz No.4 in a hot summer day.

5. For your dessert needs, Flying Monkey has the best cupcakes and lemon bars in town. Termini Brothers has a killer chocolate covered banana on a crescent cookie. You can also visit the ladies at Famous 4th for a fresh baked cookie. For something completely evil, you can go to the Amish bakery for a cinnamon roll with nuts AND frosting.

6. Shanghai Gourmet's American Chinese food is as good as any place in Chinatown. Try their fried rice or the Shrimp in Lobster Sauce, it's not on their menu but the jumbo shrimps in the silky luscious sauce is to die for. (gulp)

7. The Spice Terminal will fulfill most of your gourmet needs. Bee Natural has a wide variety of honeys. For cheese and charcuterie, you can visit Salumeria and if not for anything else, go to By George for their pasta sauces, they'll even sell you pizza dough if you want to make something at home. 

It's a vibrant place with lots of other places to discover and it's a great place to walk and browse when you have the time. Just don't stand in the middle of the aisle and block traffic, it can be crowded. Cell phone reception can be on the low side, and it's hard for the working folks to pick up groceries on their way home since most of the shop will close business around 5, but there's the weekend. The Amish generally won't be there from Sundays to Wednesdays but most shops open Mondays to Saturdays and some even open on Sundays.

text:
If I lived in Philly, I'd be living in the RTM!!! Yup, LIVING there! I was that fascinated. I love love love small vendors cooking up incredible, delectable bites. The croissant at Market Bakery was sooo good! It was flaky, buttery, delicious! I was a little sad that I had to share one with my boyfriend. Capuccino at Old City Coffee, yep, definitely 5 stars. It was strong, rich, foamy and piping hot. I struggle with this temperature issue at lots of coffee joints, including Starbucks. I want my coffee to be hot when it is served. I can adjust it to be less hot, if I want. I can't go the other way!
I digress. 
The cajun shrimp and crab pasta salad was good but I couldn't find any crab in it. The cheesesteak at Carmen's, DELISH! We got ours with roasted hot pepper and mushrooms. The heat was a definite plus!
Finally, Bassett's icecream was a good way to end brunch. 
Definitely coming back here when I visit Philly again!

text:
I remember wandering through Reading Terminal Market once several years ago, but I don't remember being all that enamored.  I'm pretty sure this was before I turned into a Food Network junkie, before I ever cooked for myself, before I had any kind of appreciation for fresh, quality ingredients, and certainly long before I began Yelping.

What my friends and I thought would be a pretty quick trip turned into a two-hour exploration.  Because it was a Sunday morning, the Amish vendors were closed, but since I have yet to sample their wares, I didn't miss them.  There was plenty to choose from: produce, spices, meat, cheeses, seafood, baked goods...  Maybe it was just the novelty of the place, but I felt inspired to create.

When we had finally filled our shopping bags with various fresh finds, we decided to get something prepared to eat.  We ended up at Kamal's Middle Eastern Specialties, where I tasted my first falafel and lamb shawerma.  Delish!  We ended at Flying Monkey Patisserie where, forced with too many choices, I ordered a brownie to eat at that moment, plus 4 different cupcakes to take home.

Since there are less merchants open on Sundays, RTM was not that crowded during my visit.  I was satisfied with the choices that remained, but am definitely curious enough about what wasn't open to brave what I hear will be a pretty chaotic weekday.

text:
Impression:They always list this place as a top 10 thing to do in Philly and it's a no wonder! If you've been to Seattle's Pike Market, then this is a more urban and New England version of it. It has produce from farms, heritage varieties, fresh eggs, cheddars, deli, meats, and bakeries that offer mouth watering pastries. There's also a large variety of food stands and stalls that offer a very impressive variety of foods from barbecue, to breakfast, desserts, Indian, African, and Hillel foods. 

Prices- That's what everyone always wants to know especially if it's a tourist attraction. So in terms of produce, it's not bad priced. Not as high as whole foods, but certainly not your Italian Marketplace where you can haggle your way down to pennies. One can probably get some quality farmer produce for a reasonable price of like 1.99$/lb for apples or 2 for 1$ corn to give an idea of the ballpark range. The food is also pretty reasonable priced. You can get a whole lunch set for less than 10$ and the portions are large. You can order most foods for less than 10$ here. 

Hours- so this place is open until 6 pm on most days, so if you're going to go, do not bank on this place on being your dinner place, because chances are most of the produce will have been sold off, stalls are closing, and you may be left with whatever is leftover (meaning smaller selection). I recommend hitting this place for lunch or even late afternoon stop as you wrap up your activities. 

Food: What to try- there are a few places that have their original site outside the marketplace. Meltykraft and Metropolitan Bakery have their own stand alone branches outside of this marketplace for example, so I recommend trying places that cannot be found outside- this may require a little more research, but the Indian food place for 9.99$ lunch set looked amazing and line moved fast. The Amish desserts are also a hit here as well. 

Amount of time recommended- you can probably spend a couple of hours in this establishment. It is massive and overwhelming. It has almost everything, so don't go in starving because you'll probably just wind up sitting at the first place you see and stuffing your face and then be sad you can't put down the amazing looking treats ahead.

text:
I had to leave and take a break after about an hour... it was sensory overload. So many delicious smells and sights and flavors! When I came back, I was a bit better acclimated. It's not as large or as expansive as the Mercato Centrale in Florence, but it's pretty big!
One of the mainstays there is DiNic's, which makes a revered roast pork sandwich comprised of three ingredients: Roast pork, sharp provolone and broccoli rabe. The cheese provides a tanginess and prevents the pork juice from soaking through the roll; the pork is slow-roasted and delicious, while the broccoli rabe provides some crunch and offsets the sweetness of the pork. Justifiably loved by many.
The many Amish stores there are also worth checking out; there's a fresh-made doughnut shop that's excellent and a country-style diner that serves breakfast fit for powering field hands.
I had a great time there and would urge anyone to spend time there, especially on your first trip to Philly.

text:
There is so much in this market and everyday my wife and I walked through it we noticed  something new. 

If you are there for the Apple Dumplings make sure you don't go on Sunday as the Dutch side of the market is not open on Sunday's. 

I tried Tommy Dicnic's and I must say it was a great sandwich. We got there for lunch and the beef brisket was not in stock. I must say, do a little research on how to order your sandwich. This helped us be able to order quickly and feel comfortable about what we ordered.

The pork sandwich, wet, with broccoli rabi and cheese was a HIT! It was large enough for two of us to split it as a snack. We decided to try multiple things around the market.... Don't let the long lines scare you..

DICNIC'S TIP: If you find a seat at Dicnic's sit down and you won't have to wait in line!!!!

Overall, there is so much in this market it is hard to explore in one day. Take an appetite and try a little bit of everything! You won't be upset!

text:
This place was so much fun. There was so much to try. The homemade ice cream was amazing as well as the sample of chicken pot pie soup and lemonade I tried. Oh and the homemade carrot bread. A huge assortment of fresh products. It was fun watching some of the Amish making stuff from scratch. And the thing that shoots out rice cakes. It was packed on a Saturday for an early lunch, but pretty dead when we came back on Sunday for breakfast since the Amish and most of the other vendors were not there. They also had farm animals and music outside when we were there on Saturday. 

I wish I had a place like this closer to home. I will be back next time I'm in Philly!

text:
Wow, what a an amazing place. I only had one day in Philly, so this was one of the must-stops. My bro and I decided to have some lunch here but we were having a very hard time deciding, as there were way too many tempting choices! We had to systematically go up and down all the aisles to make sure we saw all the vendors to make the best informed choice. In addition to all the prepared foods there were purveyors of all kinds of other goods, such as produce, meats, seafood, and crafty items. And all along the perimeter of the market were restaurants too--most of them chain restaurants, it looked like, but if that's more your speed it's nice to have that option. After perusing ALL our options, we finally decided to get lunch at the Wursthaus Schmitz (separate review). It's pretty hectic and crowded, as you may well imagine, but it wasn't too bad, and kind of added to the atmosphere. Fortunately they have lots of seating. 

STEPH JUDGEMENT: A sensory overload--in a good way!

text: I try to go to Reading Terminal whenever I have a free weekday afternoon.  At first this place can be incredibly overwhelming because it gets so crowded you can barley move.  This is a great place to visit with family because there is something that is bound to satisfy everyones tastes.  I wish they were open later because sometimes I want to stop by for dinner.  Parking near here is a nightmare so don't bother. Certain places aren't open on certain days (I went this past Monday and the Amish dealers were closed). My advice, pick a day later in the week and go when the lunch crowd dies down, making your trip less hectic with more options.

text:
Loved this place.  It's a conglomeration of restaurants, groceries, and other merchandise under one roof.  We enjoyed walking through the merchant stalls to see what was being offered.  They had a butchers shop, fresh fruits and vegetables, a variety of restaurants, bakeries, candy store - you name it, they probably had it there.

We ate breakfast at the The Dutch Eating Place (an amish style eatery).  There was a line, so we figured it had to be good, right?  My husband had the blueberry pancake and turkey bacon special.  He got 2 blueberry pancakes that were as big as the dinner plate they were served on.  I had the 2 eggs with toast and scrapple.  I'm not sure I'm a scrapple fan, but I had to try it...  My husband and I shared our meals and couldn't eat it all!

I'd definitely recommend checking out the Reading Terminal Market and the Dutch Eating Place.

text:
Let me be frank; I absolutely love the Reading Terminal Market. LOVE IT. It's without a doubt my favorite place to go on the weekends. It can be overwhelming being there are so many choices to eat, to shop, etc. If you can't find something you like here then there's something wrong with you.

Not only is it a great place to eat but to shop too; there are vendors that sell products other than food. 

A warning; it can get extremely crowded on weekends. Crowded as in shoulder to shoulder (the lines for the vendors can get very long, Beiler's Donuts being one of them). If you're a tad claustrophobic, like myself, it can be a little overwhelming. But worth a trip!

text:
Over the years I have naturally enjoyed the market to get a quick bite, grab some produce, or feed my sweet tooth. There are days where I walk in and can freely roam exploring what new items are in. Other days I get to see the excitement of tourist and locals "excusing" their way to a vendor in order to feed their bellies. I personally like the quieter times which is after lunch. 
Lines move quickly although and all the vendors have great service. The downside is that some vendors are overpriced but, overall it's the place to go. 

My favorite spot is the Dutch Eating Place. Great food and great service. When I worked down the street, their Turkey sandwich with gravy was my go to! Walk a little further and you can pick up Delish Hope's cookies at the Pennsylvania General Store.

text:
Holy Toledo! There are waaaaay too many food choices here. And when you're belly is grumbling it's hard to choose. There are plenty of tables where you can chill and eat. FYI, some of these restaurants do not accept credit cards. Have a stash of cash just in case. From what I saw:

-Seafood market
-Southern Jambalaya
-Sweets bakery
-Po Boys
-Sushi/Japanese
-Sandwiches
-Ice cream and fruit smoothies

And I'm sure there's more. I walked that thing twice over before I choose jambalaya and friend mac and cheese balls for my dinner. Prices are pretty average. you may be paying $10-$15/person depending on what you choose to eat and drink. 

This market is not the quietest or cleanest I've ever experienced but just having the selection made it enjoyable.

text: Best. Market. Ever. There's so much ridiculously good stuff here that you forget that one of the places is Tommy DiNic's. I live in Atlanta. I wish that instead of the Kroger or Publix they had a Reading Terminal Market near where I live. If that happened, I would certainly be triple my current body weight and basking in the glory of delicious obesity. It's almost torturous going through Reading and trying to commit to only one place! I only think that by choosing one place, I forgo another place. It's torture I tell you, torture! If you haven't been here, this should be at the top of your list of things to do in Philadelphia. Arm yourself with Tums, Pepcid, and Nexium. And enjoy it. Best. Market. Ever.

text:
Went here for Sunday afternoon snacks, around 2pm. This place is great and I'm a big fan of marketplaces like Pike Place and Chelsea Market, so I had to go visit. It's located conveniently near the Convention Center, so if you're ever in town for an event there it makes it perfect for grabbing an affordable meal. 

For a Sunday a lot of the vendors were open. It was nice to just walk around and see all the varieties of food available. It seems like they have everything  from Indian to Mexican to Kosher Deli to Crepes. Along with prepared food, there are numerous meat, cheese, produce, bread, bakeries, chocolate, etc vendors. It is a foodie's heaven as any market is.  It was pretty busy around the one entrance we came through as a produce/meat stand was right there. My companion and I setted on some fried chicken from Delilahs which I was told was beat by Bobby Flay during a Macaroni and Cheese smackdown challenge thing. Afterwards we went to Flying Monkey Bakery for brownies and walked around. There is plenty of seating, as most food stands have counter seating and there are tables and chairs located throughout the market. The only downside is that there is one bathroom and it's pretty small so you probably have to wait.  

Aside from food, there are several plant, gift, etc vendors. It's definitely a place you want to check out when you're visiting Philadelphia, especially when you are hungry and indecisive, because I'm pretty sure you'll be able to find something there! If not, then there is something wrong with you.

text:
There are a lot of positives about RTM:

There is an abundance of food options. If you're in the neighborhood and want something fast and tasty, this is a good place to go. You can choose to sit down and eat (like at Molly Malloy's) or you can grab something fast and walk around with it (Olympia Gyro).

I am also particularly fond of the home made chocolate retailers. Yum!

The main reason that we go to RTM, though, is for the humanely raised and organic meats. There are several Amish stands that specialize in selling *real* meat (not genetically modified, hormone-injected, tortured animals). You should check them out!

Parking can be a real bitch, though, so you're better off taking public transportation if you're not going to have too many bags to carry. There are also hordes and hordes of people, so if you've got social anxiety, this is NOT the place for you.

text: I just went last w/e and I forgot how cool this place is. It was a rainy miserable day and the RTM was a great place to go since it is indoors. We ate some sandwichs, bought some seafood and crabcakes for din-din, and bought way more sweet treats then we should have. There is a huge section of all Amish made cakes, pies and breads. They're cheap and so good. I didn't know it but Hope's Cookies from Rosemont even has a store here. They make really, really yummy cookies and other treats. There's a Bassett's ice cream store, too. Pretty much whatever you are in the mood to eat can be found here. This place is a lot of fun and def a must-see for people from out of town or visiting.

text:
A must for anyone visiting Philly! This is the city's main farmer's market, which is hosted within an old train shed. Its history is absolutely fascinating, and when it first opened WAY back when it held almost 400 vendors - can you imagine!

My first visit here was apparently on a "quiet" day, which basically means I had some breathing room in what was still an absolutely packed space. 

But there's a reason this place is always packed: it's fantastic. You can find EVERYTHING here if you look long enough. Breakfast food, sandwiches, gyros, sushi, bakeries, desserts, beads, an entire stand dedicated to selling flavored honey and beeswax, and of course, Philly cheesesteaks - and that's just to name a small number of the stands and types of food you can find in here; it's an absolutely amazing place to just get lost in. 

Bring your adventuring spirit and appetite when you head in here for sure, because you will get a heaping plate of food no matter where you go to eat! And give yourself pleeeenty of time to explore and enjoy the place!

text:
My first stop in Philly after dropping off my bags at the airbnb location I was staying at.

The Reading Terminal is an amazing place jam-packed with all sorts of delicious food stands, ranging from sandwich places to indian cuisine and pastries/icecream. Definitely a great place to spend a couple hours sharing different food with friends.

I stopped at a couple different locations which will have reviews to follow: Tommy Dinic's (Roast Pork Sandwich), Rib Stand (Boneless Rib Sandwich), Bassett's (Icecream).

There is also a nice selection of produce,meats,and seafood. With the seafood selection being the best of the batch. I saw some shrimp that were easily larger than the size of my hands!!

The Reading Terminal is definitely a spot you must check out for both the wide variety of food as well as the experience!

text:
I can be seen here basically 3 times a day.  

First at Le Bus bakery for my 1.25 hazelnut coffee.
Second at Hershel's Deli for my 3.09 ridiculously large in size "small Maztos ball soup.
Third picking up cheese infused with black truffle (SO good) and produce across the way at a stand that offers 10% off for college students.  

If you don't sense my enthusiasm for this market let me make it more clear for you:  I LOVE THIS PLACE.  I can get almost everything I need, and most of the time below grocery store prices.  And when the Dutch come in I think the best smells come out of that place I have ever laid my nose on.

I have said this before, this is about one of the only things I like about this god foresaken city, and bless its food filled heart.

text:
I was just in Philly for an event at the Convention Center, and ate at the Reading Terminal Market 3x for lunch.  I read the Yelp reviews and I'm shocked at how excited everyone is over the food at this place.  

Yes, the choices are endless.  And yes, it's awesome to have so many options to grab a quick lunch.  But the quality of the food, while not bad, is pretty much food court fare.  3 lunches from 3 different vendors and it was all just fair at best.  1 just plain disappointing package-tasting corned beef sandwich from an Amish vendor, 1 bready crab cake plate, and 1 hotdog that was worth every penny of $1.50.

Normally I'd be tempted to give this place 3 stars simply for the convenience and variety, Because everyone is raving about how great the food is, I'm gonna attempt to instill a little balance by tossing out a 2.

text:
Reading Terminal Market is a great place to browse and to enjoy the bustling atmosphere. I wish I had more time (and appetite) to truly enjoy this market and EVERYTHING they have to market. Come here for a huuuuuge variety of food, types of cuisine, and dessert options. 

Of all the things we could have bought, we decided to try the grilled cheese shop, due to its popularity before $8 you get an ooey-gooey cheesey sandwich with a side of refreshing and salty dill chips. Deliciousness. We don't often eat that much cheese, so we were glad to share this one sandwich. Trust me, it's rich enough. And even though it was perhaps a bit too rich for the both of us, it was totally worth it. Sooo good. 

Surprisingly, this place has a variety of grilled cheese options. It can get a bit overwhelmed, but I recommend just going for the classic. We added tomato and bacon- also a nice touch. 

Remember to event cash- not all shops accept credit cards. While there are several ATM, it's nice to bring cash ahead of time to avoid the fee.

If Reading Terminal Market were a woman I would have sweet, sweet relations with it.

text:
Simply writing a review for Reading Terminal Market does not do it justice. For those unfamiliar, RTM is a large building consisting of many small businesses and stands ranging from groceries to eateries to miscellaneous goods. Only the listing on their website or a visit in person can give an accurate feel of the scope. 

Overall, the place is clean and you're able to find just about anything food-related you might have a craving for. Be prepared for an overload of options and  to spend a good deal of time here- even a simple walkaround can take an hour or two. Most businesses and eateries have their own review pages and websites for those curious. 

Two important things to note: 1) The Pennsylvania Dutch retail section is not open the same hours as the entire market due to their beliefs and scheduling. This section is normally only open Wednesday to Saturday. 10+ of the stands are qualified as PA Dutch, Amish, or Mennonite and as such missing them is a significant chunk of the market.

and 2) Parking is generally done in garages near to the market, though it can get expensive quickly. Even locals are sometimes unaware that if you do end up making a purchase, ask the vendor to validate your parking ticket for a significant reduction on 2 hrs of parking. (Though still not free)

text: Reading Terminal Market does have a few hidden gems, but overall it's not a huge stand out to me. I LOVE Hope's Cookies and the Amish Market (their BBQ is AWESOME). I haven't really been wow-ed by the other vendors in RTM. The produce is hit or miss. Flying Monkey has NEVER had red velvet cupcakes when I stopped by. You'd think for such a popular flavor, they would make a larger quantity per day. The other food vendors are okay, but nothing worth going out of your way for. Avoid RTM at lunch time since that's when it's plagued with tourists and convention goers. So in short, when you hit up RTM, stream line for Amish BBQ followed by Hope's Cookies and you won't be disappointed.

text:
Having grown up in an area where Farmers Markets were an everyday event (2 separate daily markets and one weekly) in my hometown. These days you can find some really good weekly Farmers Markets in many towns and, occasionally you find a daily like the Reading Terminal Market.

We walked in and I was home again. The hustle and bustle of vendors setting up, the aroma of fresh baked Artisan bread, the smell of just brewed hot coffee - mixed with the occasional off-scent of freshly butchered meat or fish - totally transformed my world for a few minutes from hectic "day-to-day-today" to a more bucolic boyhood.

If you want it, Reading Terminal Market most likely has it. From eats to sweets to handmade chocolate treats and handmade crafts. Sit down and enjoy a cup of distinctively fresh coffee while watching the scurrying workers around you. Or grab a breakfast or lunch from one of the many stands set up and waiting for you to sample their fares.

There is simply too much to describe in one brief review, so I strongly encourage you to go and see for yourself. It's a step back in time with some modern adaptations on the market I so fondly remember.

text:
Price: As every Farmer's market will be, it has its ups and downs. Some places are pricey; others offer a bag of vegetables for a dollar (making avocados a steal.)

Variety: Well, you can get everything from silly home decor (liberty bell christmas ornaments and chocolate phillies logos?) to Carmen's $$ Cheesesteaks, to amish pretzel dogs, seafood, soup, and lebanon bologna. There are your token candy corners and vegetables galore, and it's a great place for jams and jellies, especially those kinds you're not used to seeing in Philly (mint, mulberry...)

I'm from the country and Reading Terminal is a step into the markets at home, with the smell of cheesebox wood and butter and dill pickles and deli meats. You'll get personal service and an assortment of Appalachian to Jersey coast accents :)

text:
This is the number one visited tourist spot in Philadelphia. Please do not let the word "tourist" deter you. There is every kind of food you can think of here and some you didn't. A few of my favorite spots:
-Hershel's, (or Uncle Hershel's as me and my siblings like to call it) stop here for the best reuben of your life.
-Beiler's donuts will make you a believer.
-Kamal's has the absolute best falafel I've ever tasted and amazing fresh juices and smoothies.
-a trip to reading terminal is not complete without a stop to Bassett's for some Philadelphia-style ice cream.

I could seriously write about this place all day. Take the train or bus if you don't want to deal with traffic and parking. If you park in the garage directly across the street with the big sign that tells you it's discounted if you get it validated inside, it's not lying. If you have a few people with you and don't mind driving in city traffic, it is definitely a bargain.

Another tip is on Sundays some of the vendors are closed due to religious beliefs, but a lot of the other good spots are opened and it is usually not quite as crowded as a Saturday.

text:
Can't imagine saying anything bad about RTM.  If you want to avoid tourists, the best times to go are on weekday mornings.  My husband and I love coming here for before-work breakfast dates.  Sometimes, we stop at Schmucker's to get gluten-free breakfast sandwiches (Moses and his wife are amazing people).  Then, we get our coffee from Flying Monkey in the next aisle.  You also can't go wrong with Downhome Diner.

I also love RTM for groceries.  Iovine's is great for produce.  I also love Fair Food--they host the Lancaster Farm Fresh CSA, but also have a nice market (Weckerly's ice cream sandwiches = so, so good) and very lovely staff.

text:
Eric B's review and mention of Philly made me HAVE to review this.. esp. since a coworker is about to enter grad school @ UPenn soon... 

Go to this adorable, kickbutt market if ever you're in town to enjoy the sights and history of Philly. Everything that you could possibly think of is here... er, dare I timidly suggest, the Pike Place of the East Coast sans all the fishmongering shows?

One amazing time, trying to thaw by nipping into places intermittently... have gone for a visit to "Brotherly Love" land  in the dead of winter...still, so thoroughly thrilled to have run into the Terminal Market after a visit to the train station (and, of course, to Chinatown!)

Wink; thanks Eric!

text:
This is one of my happy places in Philly. As I'm sure it is for lots of locals and tourists alike.

Some of my fave stops: Termini for cannoli, Beiler's for doughnuts and cookies, Kamal's for Middle Eastern food and smoothies, Salumeria for some of the best hoagies in town, Fair Food Farmstand for quality (though pricey) local produce, DiNic's for roast pork sandwiches, and several great butchers and seafood vendors. 

Wish I had a bottomless belly to hit up all these places at once!

text: This is a haven for people who love ethnic food. May be the best place in Philly for its variety and potential for one-stop shopping. There must be at least 50 booths here, and virtually every ethnic group is represented here. There are numerous fruit and vegetable stands supplying any veggie fruit, nut, several fish mongers, a terrific  spice shop, delicious pastry and bread booths,  a kitchen gadget shop,  sandwich places, e.g.  Most of the food is fresh and house-made. The used book stand is somewhat pricey, but the books are interesting and unusual. There is even a booth that sells only cook books.  I found that a good time to shop is on Monday morning before lunchtime. You can usually get a seat if you wish to sit down with your food and the isles are not as crowded. Try to allow a few hours there, as it will take you that long to explore all the Market has to offer. Have fun!

text:
This is my favorite thing about this city. The terminal market has everything you would ever need. It's a place in which you can dabble in all your guilty pleasures. 

This market has everything from homemade pickles to cheeses to fudges to pancakes to fresh bread to gyros to cheese steaks. If you want to eat it, this market has it. 

The lines are long but the people watching is endless so time flys by faster than you expect even in some of the longest lines you will probably stand in. This is one of my all time favorite markets. 

Beiler's donuts is a must. It's one of the most spongy and bouncy donuts you will eat. They make the donuts right in front of you! Try the apple fritters!!! This place has a line that passes Dutch eating place and the fudge shop. 

This market has bee wax candles to little gift shops. It pays to stop by this market to pick up some little gifts and keepsakes. 

Another place you have to try is the Dutch eating place. The restaurant has great specials. Get their Ruben sandwich. This place is a must for breakfast.

One place I do not recommend is tommy dinic's. This place makes me angry cause I waited in line for so long just to get a low quality sandwich. I was expecting their sandwich to be delicious because of all the hype. I was a bit confused as to why people were so excited about this place. I really was so confused and I am still confused by it. I also feel like I will forever be confused as to why people are so infatuated by this place. It's really not worth the wait nor is the hype real. They don't have a huge depth of flavor profiles in their sandwich. I give dinic's two stars. But their service is quick and very friendly. 

Overall, this market is a must when in the city. It's worth your time and all the extra pounds you will most definitely gain.

text:
This place is a SIX STAR!  We traveled north on the recommendation of pretty much everyone from Philadelphia and the multi hour drive was well worth it.  As we arrived late we didn't have much time, but we ordered a pretzel, a felafel, some chocolate and bought a few sausages for the road as well.  All of it: A+.

Pretzel beat out the NYC street pretzel, which surprised me (though it's far lower profile) - lower salt and more substantial.  The felafel was awesome, though I'm sure you can get a good one everywhere these days.  That one was particularly delicious - lots of greens.  

Great on price, super high quality.  Great environment with must be hundreds of different establishes.  I'd say this is the strong equivalent of Fanheuill Hall in Boston, Mass and that it probably has no equivalent on the East Coast.  To me worth a trip from wherever

Minor quibble.  We were there at closing and the custodians truly shove you out the door.  So be sure to get everything done with some time to spare.  Everyone's nice until closing time, don't expect to beat the clock and make out big because...they really push you out. Literally.

text:
When you get a free day to walk and explore a single building in downtown Philly, come with some cash and an empty stomach. You won't want to miss out on some of the great eats inside Reading Terminal and be a part of the hustle and bustle of the marketplace.

Some things that really sucked about coming here, the parking was ridiculous. I went on an off-day and it was still super busy and the structure (where I ended up parking) was pretty expensive. I felt really rushed to eat my food then get out. Next time, I'll have to try really hard to find street parking or maybe even a paid lot which is cheaper than the structure. Also, inside, you pretty much have to fight for a seat and hold down the fort while your friends order and bring the food because even though there's a lot of seating, there's a lot more people.

If you can walk down here and park further away and don't mind searching for a table/seats then this is a really cool place to check out.

Parking: Structure across the street $6/30mins or limited 2-hour street parking

text:
Everybody talks about Reading as if it's a national treasure but I am sometimes let down by the market.  It's not that it's a good idea to have such a wide breadth of local flavor all in one place it's the execution that's lacking.  

What I mean is that most of the local flavor is represented but it's represented poorly meaning that most of the food is mediocre which is too bad considering you can walk a couple blocks to get the best of (insert food style).  In most cases, it's not who makes the best of a certain type of food but who can afford to pay the rent there.  What would really make the pace special is if they chose the top vendors as opposed to whoever can pay the most rent.  

The other issue, and this is a big one, is the lack of being open on Sunday.  This is really a chicken/egg issue.  Are most businesses closed on Sunday because of lack of business or is there a lack of business because most of them are closed?  All I know is this seems to be an epidemic in what is a city the size of Philadelphia.  In order to attract people into the center of city during the weekend, it has to be open first.  I understand that many of the businesses have religious reasons for not working on the Lord's day but this is akin to Chinatown shutting down one day a week in New York.  This is supposedly a world-class city so why does it feel like I'm in the middle of the midwest when I'm in Center City on a Sunday?

For me, it was sampling some German for lunch (Bavarian sausage sandwich), since for the most part, that it not easy to find where I currently live.

Of course, at peak lunch hour, finding open seating can be tough, though generally no worse than in any urban market in any major city I've visited.  The staff seems to make a really good effort to keep the Market clean, despite the volume of patrons.

Our group browsed around for a while, sampling some 'Old City Coffee' and of course a few sweets.  The dark chocolate pretzels were the perfect dessert for me!

text:
I love public markets and so Reading Terminal Market was a must-do on my visit to Philadelphia. RTM is a huge public market with a lot of vendors - there are an overwhelming amount of options! From fresh produce, to seafood, to meat, to cheese, you can get almost anything here! You can get pastries, coffee, tea, ice cream,  Pennsylvania Dutch, Chinese, Thai, Mexican, Cajun, burgers, cheesesteaks, and more! There's even an oyster bar inside. Great variety! 

Stopped in at lunchtime on a weekday and the place was just packed with people everywhere. No surprise that it's a popular stop for locals and tourists to get some lunch. The line at Beiler's Donuts was the longest, as was the line for Hershel's East Side Deli. There are communal seating areas, but at lunchtime the tables were filled. I came back the next day early in the morning and while not everything was open, there were definitely less people and less chaotic. 

What I was most interested in was the Pennsylvania Dutch businesses. There's a sign by the Dutch Eating Place that says the hours for the Pennsylvania Dutch merchants being Tuesday or Wednesday through Saturday, closing up at 3PM on Tuesdays and Wednesdays and closing up at 5PM Thursdays, Fridays, and Saturdays. But I was there on a Monday and Beiler's was definitely in operation, though Dutch Eating Place was closed. Aside from Beiler's and the Dutch Eating Place, there's also Miller Twist that has soft pretzels and ice cream, and Riehl's which has cheeses, and Smuckers which supposedly is famous for their pot roast sandwiches. Other Pennsylvania Dutch vendors sell crafts and jams and honey. I returned the following day on a Tuesday to eat at Dutch Eating Place (separate review). 

Overall, RTM is a fun place to visit and a great option if you're not sure what you want to eat - there's bound to be something you're craving if you walk around long enough. I tried tea from the Tea Leaf, tea from Old City Coffee, ice cream from Bassetts, jambalaya from Beck's Cajun Cafe, a donut from Beiler's, a soft pretzel from Miller's Twist, and breakfast from Dutch Eating Place. Wish I stayed in Philly longer, so I could've tried even more stuff!

text:
I see where people are coming from, calling it a tourist trap, but I don't think that's completely accurate as I know many locals including myself who enjoy stopping by. At times it can get overwhelmingly crowded with people squeezing and shoving in the narrower halls, so I try to come at off times. 

It's like LA's Grand Central Market, a massive building filled with all kinds of vendors. There's fresh produce, every cuisine ranging from Indian to Cajun, kitchenware, spices, butchers, and bakeries. Now that's not to say that all of the vendors are good. Honestly, I've found the food to be pretty hit or miss, and the vast majority to be average. Maybe I'm missing the good places, but I still like this place for its vibe even if not for its food.

text:
I haven't been here in a while so decided to hit it up for lunch.  Finally today worked out for my friend and I and we walked there a few blocks.  Hitting the terminal at noon... uhhh not a good idea.  It was packed.  I wanted everything but couldn't decide on anything.  I could have spent 20 minutes just cruising around the fresh flower stand.  The place is just great.  It was so crowded though and working with an hour for lunch wasn't an ideal situation for what all of my senses were yearning for -- which was in fact everything.

BUT -- I ended up at this "Everyday Gourmet" stand - mostly because there was no line.  I got the most delicious and perfect lunch for what I was craving (it's a monday, folks, I needed vitamins in the veggie form).  The portabello mushroom topped with this cheese and artichoke concoction that looked like a crab cake was stunningly divine.  Heated up and blessed with some fresh spring mix on the side, I was loving it.  It was so tasty.  Even if I did have to eat it while sitting on a wall outside, I was pleased.

My friend and I are going back but only when we have hours to spend amongst the many stands/smells/tastes.  If you haven't been there in a while, it's definitely worth the trip.

text:
When in Philly, this is a MUST! I'm so sad that today was my first time coming here after being in Philly multiple times. What was I doing with my life??

This place has everything you could want (and more). And that could even be a problem for people like me, who are bad at making decisions. I think I walked around the whole place twice before deciding on somewhere to eat.

Everything, everywhere looks so good! I honestly can't even remember the place I ended up eating, but I had lobster mac and cheese and a cob kind of salad. SO. GOOD. I also got some coffee from the coffee place near main, front entrance. Also SO GOOD. They had handcrafted syrups!!

I wish I had more time in Philly or lived somewhere close because besides places to eat, the reading terminal also has lots of produce, delis, and other local/homemade things.

I stopped at a couple of the sellers and purchased some candles and honey! 

Really great place. The only bad thing is obviously it does get crowded and I imagine at certain days and times, it's hard to find somewhere to sit so you can eat.

text:
We were in Philadelphia staying at the Hilton Garden Hotel and asked the front desk if there was someplace good to eat within walking distance.  They recommended the Reading Terminal Market and said it was just around the corner.
We had no idea what this was but took the walk and was pleasantly surprised to find everything inside. Tons of places to eat about anything anyone could want, a market, bakery, etc.....
We chose the deli and opted for the corned beef sandwich.  It was huge and tasted fantastic.  There are so many choices that you could go there every day and have something totally different each day.  
The Reading Terminal Market is certainly a place to stop, especially if you have a group of folks with different tastes.  
It is a bit hectic inside and not easy to maneuver around the place but there is no shortage of interesting things to find inside.
We would definitely go there again the next time we are in Philadelphia.

text:
There are so many different places to eat in here than it would be difficult to review them all.  Let's put it this way, do you want vegetarian food?  Fresh farm meat?  Eggs?  Cookies?  Cakes?  Cake baked my mennonites?  Thai food?  Falafel?  Ice Cream?  Spices?  Tea?  Coffee?  A burger?  A cheesesteak?  A vegetarian cheesesteak?  Pretzels?  Candy?  Used books?  A public restroom?  Flowers?  Fresh fruit?  Fresh organic fruit?  Fresh vegetables?  Fresh organic vegetables?  Milk?  Soy milk?  Breakfast?  Lunch?  Dinner?  A convenient place to meet a friend?

I think you get the point...

No matter what want in the food department you can get it here!  And if you have a wide diversity of friends who all like to eat different things then bring them here and they'll all find something.

One note: it tends to be very crowded during the lunch hours, as half of downtown comes here for lunch!

text:
Visiting Philly from California. This is our first time staying at the Residence Inn Marriott which is two blocks away from Reading Terminal Market. 

The Market closes at 6:00pm which we thought was unusual. We would have loved for it to stay open until at least 8:00pm, preferably 10:00pm. At 4:00pm the Amish bakery in the back of the Market offers many baked goods for $2.00. We bought half of a pumpkin cheesecake pie for $2.00, simply amazing. The pie was delicious! The sweet girl behind the counter would not accept a tip.

So many choices So little time. We walked around the marketplace and sampled different flavors of hummus, cheese, curd, and more. We were tempted by the many wonderful smells wafting through the market. 

Apparently the Bieler's Bakery is a popular place for donuts and people were standing in a long line to purchase. 

When you enter the Market, there is a welcome/information desk which was manned both times were there. People were stopping by to ask for directions or other questions.

The Market is a stop on the Big Bus tour.

text:
It's surprisingly delightful when a new route to the office causes me to discover (or in this case, rediscover) places in the city. 

I've been coming to RTM since I was in diapers, when the visit required a trip into the city on the R2. Now that I'm in the city, I go often. Usually to grab a crepe for lunch, pick up produce, a preztel from the Amish folks, Bassetts ice cream and any number of other delicious items. But, I can't remember every having gone into the Market before 9AM. 

But, walking from the eastern edge of the Art Museum area, to Independence Hall this morning, I realized that all of my usual coffee stops were no longer on my way to the office. What to do? Of course, there was an Old City Coffee in RTM - but was RTM open at 8:15am? 

Yes, and I think I knew that, I just never tested it out. 

RTM is an entirely different place in the morning - sleepy, warm, free of all the jostling tourists and hoardes of jury duty-ers. Half of the stands are open or are in the process of opening. People behind the counters look up as you walk by and give you a cheerful smile. There are distinct smells of this or that, not the mix and match you get later in the day. After I picked up my coffee, I walked through the entire place to the last door and the only thing I had to dodge was a guy carrying a crate of produce on his head and an older woman buying fish. 

I think I'll be making a habit of this.

text:
I've been to Reading Terminal Market a few years back and to be honest, nothing was really memorable because I don't remember what I ate there. I think I faintly remember trying the roast pork sammie from Tommy DeNic's but even if I did, I can't remember what it tastes like. So this time around, I decided to document everything, so that if I do visit Philly again, I'll know what to get (or what not to). Here is everything we ate:

Tommy DeNic's: Roast Pork with Provolone and Broccoli Rabe - this was a nice break from the cheesesteaks that we've been eating. The pork was cooked perfectly, and there was a good amount of provolone and broccoli rabe. It does get messy though, so it's not really a sammie that you could eat on the go.

MeltKraft : Melter Skelter ('Melter Skelter' Raclette 3 Month, pickled green tomatoes, jalapeo, BBQ potato chips, and watercress) - this was good, but not worth $9. I don't know what it is about grilled cheese, but I just can't find a grilled cheese anywhere that's worth paying $10 for.

Beiler's Doughnuts - bought a few doughnuts from here - one crumb, the second cinnamon, and the third I can't remember. This had the longest line. The line wraps around other stands. People seem to buy these doughnuts up by the dozen. My boyfriend really enjoyed the doughnuts but to be, they were just doughnuts. But then again, maybe it's just because I'm not a huge fan.

Herschel's: Corned Beef Sandwich - although I only tried a few bites, the corned beef was pretty good. It wasn't overly salty, like corned beef tends to be. The pickles are great.

Overall, the market is a great place to try out a bunch of different foods. But it'll cost you.

text:
First off, if you live in Philly - or if you're just visiting - and you've never been here, you absolutely must go. This is an excellent place to get meat and produce for shopping- especially if you want fresh seafood- and it is an equally excellent place to stroll around, snack, grab a coffee, and browse.   (On that note there is a book store tucked in the back of the market that has an incredible selection especially if you're into esoteric, occult, or off-the-beaten-path type material. Some of it is downright bizarre- I found a book here by The Black Dot that talks about the "hidden Qabbalistic and sacred geometries of hip hop", which veers periodically into unfounded but entertaining rants about sacred Egyptian magicks.) 

Really, there isn't much I can say about the Reading Terminal Market that isn't good, unless if you're agoraphobic. Also, if you go here with friends and don't have a cell phone, expect to spend half of your time trying to figure out where the hell they are.

text:
If you are visiting Philadelphia and are not sure of what to eat, Reading Terminal Market is easily the best place to start! My uncle suggested I go there and I could not be more grateful! 

Lots of shops for touristy things to buy, t-shirts, small kitchen items, etc. Lots of choices for food to eat and food to use in your own cooking. It really is the largest and most unique market I've ever seen! If only supermarkets would go away and be replaced by thousands of Reading Terminal Markets (although it would lose a little bit of its appeal.)

My favorite spots were Famous 4th Street Cookie Company, Beiler's Bakery, Dutch Eating Place, Sweet as Fudge Candy Shoppe, Lancaster County Dairy, Bee Natural, 12th Street Cantina, Dienner's Bar-B-Q, and Kamal's Middle Eastern Specialities.

The Amish merchants are without a doubt some of the best foods I have ever eaten and what makes the market so special. I ended up buying 2 pounds of various chocolate fudges from Sweet as Fudge, 2 dozen doughnuts from Beiler's, an open faced turkey sandwich from Dutch Eating Place, a Strawberry Orange Lemonade from Lancaster County Dairy, and 3 chocolate chip cookies from Famous 4th Street Cookie Company. 

If you are driving in, make sure to get your parking validated when you spend at least $10 and can park in the garage on Filbert Street for just $4 up to 2 hours. You won't find a better deal for parking anywhere else in the city. When you don't have anything else planned, you can easily spend an entire day here and you'll love every minute of it!

text:
So, how do you review an entire market!? I'll try.

First off, if you haven't been to similar markets in other cities, let me warn you that much like other ones, this place is packed. People that live here often visit it in addition to out-of-towners.

Unlike markets in other towns, many of the prices can't be beat. Grocery shopping and butchers sell at below market value a good amount of the time so it's hard to avoid going for fresh food. Grab some muffalata or alligator sausage. Also, unlike other markets, it can be hard to walk around at times. I've pushed a stroller through the past couple years without issue (despite my phobias), but unless you're used to all the people, it can be overwhelming.

Nonetheless, the smells and sights are more overwhelming, in a good way. When family comes to visit, they always want to hit Reading Terminal, which should tell you something.

text: Really fun place to go for me on weekends. I like to stand outside for a few minutes and listen to the one-man-band with the electric guitar, harmonica, and bells attached to his foot. This guy represents all things Philadelphia. If anyone deserves a dollar or two outta my wallet, it's this guy (and I do give him something every Saturday). Inside the market is pretty crowded, but if you like food, you'll get over it. Just be careful ordering something you need to sit down for - make sure you already have a seat before you order it or else you'll be walking to Suburban Station food court to sit. There's a lot of energy and a coffee/cookie stand at the one entrance that serves cups of coffee for $1 (at least on Saturdays) and it tastes really good, too.

text:
A must if you are in Philly.You can spend the day just roaming around the market. You can find your traditional Philly steak sandwiches to Indian food. What ever you are craving you will find it here and for cheap. There is even a all philly veggie steak sandwich.

My faves at the Reading Terminal Market:
DiNic's (either the roast pork or beef with provolone, and sweat peppers)
I dont know the name of the place buts its the only one that sells roast chicken ( wings, leg quarters, or whole or half chickens)
The Dutch Corner of the Market...

The Dutch Corner closes earlier that the rest of the market. I believe close time is 5pm.

If you go to the Market right before it closes you can find good deals on pastries.

$.75 to $1.00 per cookie vs $10.00per pound (each cookie is pretty heavy)
2 for $3.00 pastries when they normally go for$3 plus.

The only restaurant  I didn't care for was the Cajun restaurant.

The lines seemed to stretch forever. And even when you got food (or if), there was barely any room to sit down and eat. The place overall felt dirty and shabby. I expected something like I saw at Chelsea Market in New York, but this was disappointing.

I did find a nice lotion/soap stall that sold me a chai spiced chapstick though :)

I got into the longest line that I could find, and later found out that I was standing in the line at DiNic's.  I got their famous pork sandwich, and it was good.  The wife also gave me some of her leftover shrimp Po boy sandwich.  Awesome place.  Too bad, I will probably never go to Philly again.

text:
Reading Terminal Market MIGHT, just might, be as good as it gets. 

On a recent trip to Philadelphia I walked in and spent a good two hours walking around. I had to get a refreshment. The sheer variety of everything--bakeries, flowers, fresh meat, seafood, restaurants, Pennsylvania Dutch merchants, coffee shops, dry goods, groceries, etc etc etc--is pretty mind-blowing. 

I ate at Tommy DiNic's (delicious). I got a slice of marbled cheesecake from Termini Brothers Bakery. I sampled some delicious cheese. There was a delightful old woman playing piano in the center of all the hustle, and I bought a hand-knitted hat from Anastasia, who was from Siberia. Hershels East Side Deli, I'll be back for you. 

If you're a tourist in Philadelphia and especially if you're a foodie tourist in Philadelphia, Reading Terminal Market is a must-visit. Come hungry!

text:
It's like the Italian market on the north side... but better! (sorry south philly)

pros!
1. very good selection of fruit and veggies never a bad apple in the bunch, literally. 
2. cheap, well depends on what you're going for. but even if it's expensive its good quality so worth the price!
3. food is good, quick service. ive eaten at several places and the staff is always friendly and helpful. theyre never impatient if you dont know what you want and always have a smile on their faces.
4. it doesnt feel like Philadelphia in here... its like ive died and gone to polite heaven where it smells like sweet sweet baked goods, organic chocolate milk, fresh cheeses and the floors have been swept!
5. tables outside! i love outdoor seating... 
6. theres a wine and spirits near by... can we say wine and cheese date?

cons...
1. during the weekends its always packed with tourists so if u know where you have to go, get there fast and dodge the little children as safely as possible!
2. during lunch time the tables indoors are always packed! you have to hunt them down and wait patiently, get warm food at your caution.. be prepare to have warm soup.
3. during conventions at the hotel right across the street this can be a hard place to get into.. with everyone standing on the sidewalk with nothing to do... i cant stand people who do this in the city. 
4. their hours.. sometimes i wish they were open later but thats why this place is so wonderful i have to plan to get there on time. and even though its not around the corner from me, i love making the trip down there.

text:
Show me anywhere else in the US that hosts an annual scrapple fest. Show me a market that has space to spread out tables, build a stage, and host an eclectic crowd of Amish scrapple men, family-owned scrapplers, and a few oddball scrapple enthusiasts wearing scrapple-themed t-shirts.

I'm from New England. We don't eat scrapple there.  On April 21st, I was schooled in scrapple by this crowd of pork-and-cornmeal mush-loving mid-Atlanticals. I watched in wonder as a table of judges assessed the entries in various categories. I tried the turkey scrapple, which I found quite delicious. I did not find the 'wedding cake' made from turkey scrapple to be as appealing.

RTM offers more than just scrapple, of course. For an out-of-towner wanting to eat as many Philly classics in as brief a time as possible, there is no better stop than the market. Don't forget to stop at the Amish pretzel joint - brushed with butter and fresh from the oven, they are a must-eat.

text:
I love the concept of this place! It's a huge market with tons of vendors, both restaurant type vendors and produce and meat vendors. 

We went on a Sunday when we were traveling for work and a lot of vendors were still there but there were definitely some places that we closed. We also tried to go the last time we were in the area, but it was Labor Day and the market was closed. 

We tried to get small amounts of food from several vendors and almost all of it was really good. 

As an added bonus, they validate parking for the garage across the street. You just take your ticket to one of the vendors you purchase something from and they'll validate it for you. It doesn't cover the entire cost, but it's significantly cheaper. 

If I lived in the area, I would definitely frequent this place.

text:
Reading Terminal Market = Disney World for foodies

If anyone asks me the question "I'm coming to Philly, what is there to see and do?" My number one answer would be Reading Terminal Market!

It is the perfect place for families, friends, couples, etc because you will be able to find something for everyone - even the pickiest eaters.

There are tons of places and kinds of foods to eat, in addition to a beer garden that allows takeout for those who are interested.

My favorite place to eat here is Meltkraft. I love the Melter Skelter, a grilled cheese with BBQ chips as one of its delicious ingredients. 

You can go here countless times and try something completely new and different each time. I also do groceries here as you can find fresh produce, meats, and more. 

The best part is, this is all indoors so as the weather turns cold, its the perfect place to spend a day eating and people-watching.

text: The variety of food here didn't fail to amaze me; it reminded me a lot of my motherland, Thailand where they have fresh food markets, and not a second goes by without it being jammed pack. I LOVE that kind of shock and energy that it brings you.  Right when I walked in, the smell of fresh fish and meat hit me at a special spot.  Of course it naturally invited me to buy groceries, but considering that I was on a trip and Philly is not my hometown, I settled for the hundreds of restaurants that were there. There were different types of cuisines to accomondate any ethnic group which was impressive.  However, the food was just okay. I went with four people and we all got our foods from different stations, but none of them really wowwed me. I think that mine was the best. I got my dish from a Chinese place that had hanging Peking duck. Though tasty, I most definitely had better. The prices here aren't bad at all though.  Fairly reasonable and won't break your wallet.

text:
As good as advertised. I've always wanted to check out Reading Terminal Market, and now that I have this would be the only reason I would return to Philly. This is one of my favorite food halls slash marketplaces, just for the sheer variety of vendors.

I spent about 3 hours just eating my way through breakfast and lunch, and purchased a variety of food to take back home. I'm sure coming on a weekday during the earlier hours before lunch helped improve my experience as well, because if the place was packed with crowds on a hot day it would be pretty miserable.

text:
THE iconic food market of Philadelphia, you simply can't go wrong if you choose to eat here! A foodie haven, you can find everything from ice cream, chocolates, cookies, meats & cheeses, fresh seafood, vegan & veggie food and plenty more. There is a vast array of options to choose from.

If you have a strong aversion towards crowds, going here during the weekends maybe be frustrating as the lines are long and finding a place to sit maybe be difficult. But these are just small inconveniences in my opinion! 

Tip: Carry cash with you as some places are cash only!

text: I love this place! There are SO many options for food of any variety -- you will not leave hungry. You can also get produce and meats/seafood here too. I loved Sweet as Fudge (the Amish candy store, with lots of homemade chocolate candies), Beiler's Donuts (fresh hand-made donuts daily!), Dinic's (awesome roast pork sandwich). There's Mediterranean food, burgers, seafood, dessert stands, Asian cuisine, New Orleans cuisine, cheesesteaks, smoothies, and so much more. I thought the prices were also fairly reasonable! Plan to spend some time here at least during your initial visit just taking in all the sights and delicious smells! It can get crowded though, and sometimes there are big tour groups or school groups. I would recommend coming here earlier in the morning or later in the afternoon when it's not as busy.

text: This place is AWESOME. My friend (who lives in Philly) suggested I go check it out my first night in town visiting for a work trip, so I figured I'd learn about using public transportation and get myself there. I went inside and it was about 3 p.m. - and just about everybody was getting ready for the post-work rush (read: not much was happening). So I walked outside and through the streets out to see Independence Square and some of the historic buildings, which were just a few blocks up the road from it. I returned closer to 5 p.m. and it was hustling and bustling. Whether you are grabbing fresh produce or a few staples for dinner, or planning to sit down and eat dinner, Terminal Market offers an extremely impressive selection of foods, both locally and from around the world. I stopped at the German place and had a schnitzel sammie for dinner, plus bought some genuine German cookies to bring back home. There is a bar on site and plenty of places to grab food and a seat. Very cool experience that I'm glad I did!

text:
This place is a must-see if you're visiting Philadelphia. Reading Terminal Market is a huge indoor market with every kind of food stand imaginable, as well as produce, and even a restaurant. From Amish to New Orleans, to Indian, to Chinese, to Philly Cheesesteaks, you will be able to find something here. Reasonably priced small food stands with seating areas. Make sure you tour the whole place before settling on one. Or else get a little something from a few! 

You could spend a couple of hours walking around here and exploring. I wouldn't say this is better than Pike's Place in Seattle; it's different. Pike's Place has tons of fresh fish, beautiful flower displays, and is lined by small specialty shops on the outside. Reading Terminal Market has a stand or two for flowers, and has little food places nestled inside. Anyway, bottom line: great stop in Philadelphia...

text:
I love this place! I am not sure what else to say...

They have everything that you can imagine as far as food goes. Well almost everything, and even some things that are really not great as far as nutrition goes (chocolate covered cookie? Win! cheesecake brownie? Hell to the yes!) The only gripe I have about the place is that quite a few of the little stores inside have a fear of credit cards, or they set some high amount as the spending limit when using a credit card. Which is fine if you are planning on buying quite a bit of food, but it can suck when you're just trying to buy some sandwich meat. Have you ever bought $10.00 worth of sandwich meat? It goes a long way. I used to love oven roasted turkey at one point. 

I always find something new when I'm in there. Probably because every time I go in there, it's incredibly busy, so I kind of make my movements through the aisles based on the general mill of the crowd (yes, I am that lazy). I don't mind it though. Part of the joy of walking through RT is just seeing what else I can find; effectively I'm a tourist, which I'm quite fine with.

text:
The kind of food oasis the concrete desert wanderer dreams about. Just about every kind of fresh food you probably crave in the middle of a workday, and some you didn't know you wanted.

The "street signs" along the aisles are clutch, so pay attention - it's easy to forget where you saw the fresh red snapper or those mozzarella balls, since the sheer visual overload produced by so many juicy vittles is enough to scramble your guidance system.

Decent produce - there's better in the city, but not with the convenience afforded by shopping for your faves and eating them both in the same spot. The variety of cuisine collected in one place is the Terminal Market's main draw; perogies or crepes, you'll likely find some way to get your filling.

text:
I came to the Reading Terminal Market due to a recommendation from a friend, as he told me to check out DiNics for their famous Roast Pork, & Roast Beef sandwiches.
Upon seeing DiNics on a T.V. food channel, I made it a point to check out the Reading Terminal Market over the weekend. 

What can I say about the Reading Terminal Market?

Well, the best way to describe this place is - it's like a GIANT mega food court & store!!! 
You name it, they probably have it here...........all kinds of ethnic foods can be found here, as well as fresh farm produce, meats & poultry, finest seafood items, baked goods & confections.

My mission when I had visited the Reading Terminal Market was to try the sandwich from DiNics (which I accomplished), as I ended up eating both the roast pork, & roast beef sandwiches.............I really enjoyed both sandwiches, but between the two...........I gave the thumbs up to the roast pork!

While walking around the mall, I ran into another sandwich shop called - Carmen's Famous Italian Hoagie & Cheesesteaks. 
The time when I was there, I saw our island son - Barack Obama come to Carmen's to eat a cheese steak, so I figured if it was good enough for President Obama, it was a must for this island son to also give it a try too! Lol!

There is a very long history about the Reading Terminal Market, as I read a brochure about this place.............let me share a little of what I read.

Apparently back in 1892 the Reading Railroad opened the Reading Terminal Market below the tracks of their massive new train shed. The 78,000 sq. foot market held nearly 800 spaces for vendors & was touted as the "greatest food market" in the world!
By 1971, the Reading Railroad went bankrupt & the Reading Terminal Market started to decline & be in disrepair. 
Beginning in the 1980's, the Reading Company renewed attention to the market & began a turnaround of the facilities, and by 1984 trains stopped running to the station above the market and the city's commuter rail system was re-routed to bypass the old Reading Terminal. 
By 1990 the historic building was sold to the Pennsylvania Convention Center Authority, who rebuilt the market to strict historic preservation standards, and also set up a non-profit management company to run the market and maintain the historical integrity of this place.

I must say, if you're ever in Philadelphia, take sometime to check out the  Reading Terminal Market, as you should put it in your "must" list of things to do! 
Visiting the market has a lot of very cool historical value, as well coming here to try the various types of food...........it's basically a foodie lovers paradise!!!

text: I absolutely love Reading Terminal. It's a foodie's heaven and you can literally satisfy any craving you're having. Great prices and selection for produce and other goods like fish and cheese. A plethora of stands selling pre-made foods that you can eat there or take to go.  They have a fabulous selection of Amish foods that I grew up with back home. It's always pretty crowded and therefore hard to find a seat to actually eat your meal there which is a bummer. You must go to Beiler's Bakery (best sticky buns, pie, donuts and whoopie pies, oh my!) and Famous 4th St Cookies if you enjoy sweets!!! Prepare for long lines during lunch and weekends--especially at the most popular stands (DiNics, thai place, etc). Stands will validate your parking ticket for the garage across the street if you spend over $10 (i think it's $10) so you pay less for parking. All in all this place is a gem in the city and somewhere locals and tourists must go.

text:
There is absolutely nothing in this place that won't blow your mind. RTM was founded in the 1890's, and has never closed since. About a third of the shops and eateries, bakeries, etc are owned and operated by Amish people. 

Three of the businesses at Reading Terminal Market have been run by the same families since the 1890's when the market originally opened. 

The Market used to be closed on Sundays (I assume) because of the Amish people, but a few years ago they decided to keep it open. So, you can go on Sundays, just expect about 1/3 of the businesses to be closed. 

Reading Terminal Market is where you go when you want to have a food experience that you can't have anywhere else other than Philly. As a local I can tell you this is where I take people just about every time if they have never been to my city. I take them to Cosmi's or John's Roast Pork later, once their RTM induced food coma has worn off.

I won't make any specific recommendations because EVERYTHING you can eat here is worthy of 5 stars. That's why it's great. You can walk around and sample all of this amazing food from all over the world and at the same time experience the TRUE definition of what it means to enjoy Philly's best. Locals come here daily to experience what they know to be one of the best spots on earth for amazing food (yes, earth).

Enjoy!

text:
Where do I begin? This was my first stop in Philadelphia, fresh off the plane and having just had the chance to drop off luggage at my friend's house. All we knew was that we were hungry and also wanted to take in some sights. So we walked down the street and headed straight for the market. And this place was PACKED! I was not prepared for the onslaught of sights and sounds and choices. I had researched some things to try - such as the pretzels, donuts, and pork sandwich - but that barely scratched the surface of what this market has to offer. I mean, c'mon, chocolate noses! 

The first day, we tried the pork sandwich with broccoli rabe and sweet pepper and it was quite tasty. Also loved the pretzel. The donuts were unique although not my favorite, but there are definitely so many to choose from you are bound to find something you enjoy - we tried the key lime, oreo creme, and sugar. 

The next day we needed a quick breakfast and had to stop by for famous scrapple and the hot apple dumpling. When it came down to a choice of adding heavy or whipped cream, I decided to be daring and go with some heavy cream and I have never been happier with my decision! That hot apple dumpling was one of my favorite things. And scrapple was unique. I ended up adding some syrup and enjoyed it. Definitely not something I get back home!

This place is a must for both tourists and locals. Good food, good prices.

text:
I first want to say that I love food markets.  We stayed at the hotel that is right next to the Reading Terminal,so it was great.  We went on a Sunday, so a lot of the stores were not opened. 

Our first stop (before we started our day) I got a cup of coffee from Old City Coffee and tried the crepes at Profi's Creperie.  We also got a philly cheese steak from Carmen's.  The food was good and we were hungry.

Our second stop (on the way back to the hotel) we stopped and got a pulled pork sandwich from DiNic's, wings from Franks A Lot, and cupcakes from Flying Monkey.  

All in all I really enjoyed walking around in this food market.  It reminds me of Pike Place in Seattle and Borough Market in London.

text:
Honestly a little bit overrated. The food is pretty decent, except for Sang Kee which has incredible duck dishes and char siu as well. Most things are a little bit overpriced, but I guess you are paying for the experience. If you want the foodie walkthrough, here's the must hits:

Beiler's has good donuts, but lines are long. 
Bassetts has good ice cream with lots of creamy flavors. 
Dutch eating place for apple dumplings. 
DiNics for a pork sandwich (personally not a fan but others like it). 
Kamal's Middle Eastern for a mint lemonade or some other fun and unique drink. 
Sang Kee for a duck fried rice. 
Mueller for a fresh soft pretzel. 

Other people have things they like also, but these are the ones I commonly hear about- I've tried them all and they're all solid. 

Pro tip: if you are driving, you can park in the garage next door for the hotel and then get your ticket validated for free 2 hour parking by a vendor if you spend 10 dollars at their stand.

text:
I went here on a weekend. The place was slammed, but the selection was lovely. At first it looked like an Amish market, but there were other things that set it apart. It wasn't a strictly Amish market type of place. I noticed Chinese and Middle Eastern offerings as well. The line for the ladies room was ridiculously long and the crowd at the market acts like they just sucked on a bag on rotten lemons, but I digress....the food made all of the hassle worth it.

I feel like this place sums up the Philly food scene pretty well, for me at least.

Due to the fact that I made the trek to Philly, I made sure that I was going to stuff my tummy to new levels of discomfort. I started at Dinic's. The line was long, but went by pretty quick. I settled for a pork sandwich with provolone and broccoli rabe. It was pretty decent, I wouldn't cry to the sky over it, but I liked it. It set me back a little over $9...not the cheapest fast eat sandwich.

There is something about pretzels and Philly that really makes for a happy combo. I picked up a pretzel on my way out of the market...I'll review the pretzel place on its own....along with the Flying Monkey bakery.

Those three spots are some favorites in the market. I could stay there all day and stuff my fact with yummies.

text: Reading Terminal Market is awesome. You have a wide variety selection of anything to get to eat while there, to-go or grocery shopping for later. There are endless top notch food places here. The crowds/lines are well worth it though!

text: Sure, this place is fun to walk through.  But the tourists who think this is a key food place to visit in Philly are seriously missing out.  Philly is a foodie paradise with INCREDIBLE restaurants!  Venture to 13th Street to try Lolita, Barbuzzo, or Jamonera, and to see all the gorgeous little shops on the street, including the artisanal chocolates made fresh at Verde; or go to Bareburger, Bluestone Lane, PS & Co, Buena Onda Tacos, V Street, Dizengoff, etc., for casual but DELICIOUS fresh food. Go to Cafe Karma (four locations) and sit in the beautiful gardens at their locations on 22nd/Pine or 10th/Pine.  Go to Whole Foods Center City and check out the delicious food hall!  For high-end restaurants, go to Talula's Garden, Zahav, Vedge, Res Ipsa, Suraya, and more!  To explore food heaven in West Philly, go to Kilimandjaro or Manakeesh restaurants, or try Chez Yasmine food truck.  For Vietnamese, go to Nam Phong or Vietnam Restaurant on Washington.  For pizza, go to Mama Palma's, Stella's, or Giorgio's on Pine.  Go to the fabulous Saturday Farmer's Market at Rittenhouse Square or the equally fabulous Sunday Farmer's Market at Headhouse Square. In South Philly, go to any of the treasures on Passyunk Avenue or to Stargazy for British pies. You get the idea...

text:
Reading terminal is a must for both tourists and locals alike. It's one of my favorite places in the city. So many awesome food vendors, led by the Amish merchants you won't find anywhere else. Let me list the vendors that make Reading Terminal so awesome:
1. Beiler's Bakery - Best Bakery in the city
2. Beiler's Donuts - Best donuts in the city
3. Smuckers - Best Roast beef sandwich in the city
4. Dutch Eating Place - Best diner in the city, featuring the apple dumpling
5. Dienner's BBQ chicken - Best Rotisserie & BBQ chicken in the city
6. Bassets Ice Cream - Best ice cream in the city
7. Beck's Cajun - One of the best places for New Orleans food in the city
8. The Rib Stand - One of the best places for ribs in the city
9. Kevin Parker's Soul Food Caf - One of the best places for soul food in the city
10. Carmen's - One of the best places for cheesesteaks &  hoagies in the city
11. Pearl's Oyster Bar - One of the best old school seafood spots in the city

I also get my meats, fish and cheeses from Reading Terminal. High quality at some of the lowest prices in the city. My favorites are:
1. Riehl Deli & Cheese shop
2. L. Halteman Family Country Foods
3. Martin's Quality Meats & Sausages
4. Iovine Brothers Produce

I can go on and on. There are candy shops, pretzels, wine, and more... It does get extremely crowded at times, but wading through the crowd is always worth it. No matter what you have a taste for you can find it at Reading Terminal.

text:
Everything looks nice and is nice, but to sum it up it is a tourist trap. I found this place a little over rated for what it is. After my friends talking it up who are local -- I found it unfortunate to not be somewhere I might myself to usually roam. Essentially what it is a huge market inside a terminal with lot of different specialty shops and eateries. 

In Washington DC where I reside in one of the suburbs -- there is a place on a smaller scale that is similar to this that sort of has spoiled it for me to no really enjoy these kinds of places and has saturated it for me. I like Reading Terminal for what it is, but I don't know if I'd consider it a 'must see' in Philly unless you're into this sort of thing. I like it for its historical significance, but the food choices were a little less than exciting.

I will probably give it a second shot at my next return simply to say that I did get the grand experience, but like I said -- it is a huge food and flea market gathered in one confined space. Don't expect to find parking around this very easily unless you get lucky like I managed to do.

text:
Reading (pronounced "redding") Terminal is fantastic, lots of wonderful yummy things. However, there's also a bunch of people, so if you're not into crowds, do your research and figure out what time might be best to go (early morning? not weekends?). I particularly like getting the fresh squeezed/blended juices and smoothies. There are places to get produce, cheese, meats/fish, chocolates, gifts, coffee, pastries, and so much more! The prices are not particularly cheap, but it's not exorbitantly priced either. If nothing else, it's a great place to people watch. 

It's also ideally located for me, since it's right next to Chinatown, where I do my weekly grocery shopping.
