text: A wonderful place to spend a few hours. (And if you love food, you'll definitely be spending a few hours.) Beware though, as it tends to get extremely crowded. There is such a great variety of food here and so much of it is so delicious! From a variety of ice creams to Indian food to classic gumbo to fancy corndogs with toppings to Puerto Rican food to banana pudding with special flavors... the list just goes on and on. You can even get fresh, smoked bones and pig ears for your dog here. This is a definite must-visit if you're anywhere within a 20 mile radius of Philadelphia. You'll find yourself coming back quite often, as I do. The only bad thing is that it's often incredibly crowded, and because you're in such a crowded place, the seating area where you can eat food at the tables is usually extremely dirty from people leaving behind trash and crumbs and messes constantly.

text:
Do you ever just walk into a place and in every direction you look in, you see food?  I'm not talking like a basic grocery store, but like gourmet food that you can smell just by looking in its direction.  If you are a foodie, this place has everything.  EVERYTHING!!!  It is especially convenient if you are staying at a nearby hotel like the Marriott Downtown since the market is not even a block away.  

So this market is a giant warehouse, and there are vendors literally everywhere.  It has many entrances, one of them being for a diner that is the only thing open 24/7... everything else closes at 6:00.  The food isn't just limited to grocery shopping - aside from the diner, there are plenty of sit-in restaurants too (and some have happy hour!).  There are bakeries and ice cream parlors too.  This place isn't just limited to food, either - there were a few vendors for gifts and for African wear and decor as well.  

The only food I got to try was from a taco place.  It was a chicken taco with very generous portions of everything.... the sauces, the meat, the guacamole, all of it.  How did it taste?  INCREDIBLE.  If I really had money to spend, I would sample various things to take home.  It is a great market and absolutely must be checked out if you are in town.

text:
The Reading Terminal Market is one of America's largest and oldest public markets, housed since 1893 in a National Historic Landmark building.  The RTM offers the widest variety of restaurants under one roof, which includes a diverse variety of locally grown & exotic produce, locally sourced meats and poultry, plus some of the best seafood, cheeses, baked goods, ice cream and confections to be had on the East Coast!

If you are a foodie, then you can't miss a visit to the infamous Reading Terminal Market. I've been here numerous times over the years and I have yet to be disappointed. Don't miss the Amish Bakery, Beiler's, where at least the very least, you will experience some of the best PA Dutch home-style food in all of Pennsylvania!  I never visit Philly without taking advantage of an opportunity to snag a few Harvest Apple donuts from Beiler's! Best donut I've ever tasted!

My second favorite spot at RTM's has to be "The Original Turkey". It's like having Thanksgiving dinner every day! There are so many choices, you won't go home hungry! 

If you get a chance to buy a ticket to "Taste of Philly", you'll get your fill of cheese-steak, donuts, crepes, ethnic foods from all over the world, as well as some of the best desserts and confections to be found in the massive state of Pennsylvania!

text:
My family is from the Philly area and I always have to make a stop here during my visits. For me, it's more for people watching and picking up sweet treats, although Glasers Black and white cookies aren't sold here any more (the store closed in NYC). 

Pros:
1). Lots of food options, even for the pickiest eaters. 
2).  Historically interesting
3).  Grocery shopping and specialty foods
4).  Close to Jefferson Septa stop
5).  Restrooms

Cons:
1).  Although there are tons of food options here, it's not the best available in Philly. They have mediocre cheesesteaks and Asian foods that you can get better in one of the cheesesteak places (Jim's, Genos, Sonny's, etc) or in Chinatown. 
2).  Super crowded!  If you can avoid bringing a stroller, do it!  Wait times for food can be almost an hour during peak times. 
3).  Not a lot of places to sit and eat. You have to stalk the tables and wait for someone to leave. 
4).  You're paying for the touristy aspect, so prices are higher for everything. 
5).  The fish markets can ruin your appetite with the stench of fish. 

Go ahead and fall for this tourist trap at least once. It's definitely worth visiting and probably my favorite market.

text: Such a neat indoor farmer's market setup! Unfortunately, the Dutch Eating Place was closed both times I went, and DiNic's was sold out of the pulled pork sandwiches...but I was successfully able to buy some artisan truffle boxes at Chocolates by Mueller, a Philly soft pretzel and other goodies at the PA General Store, a few scoops of Bassetts Ice Cream, and wished I could still have room for Flying Monkey Bakery or Old City Coffee. Pearl's Oyster Bar looked pretty enticing as well. I could've spent all day here if I didn't have business to do. Very impressed by the array of fresh meats, seafood, cheeses, nuts, produce, baked goods, even olive oil! They even already had t-shirts commemorating the Papal Visit as of early August 2015. Surprisingly, I didn't try any of the cheesesteak places here (By George, Spataro's), just didn't have enough time to explore all of it. Too bad the Wednesday and Saturday morning Taste of Philadelphia Market Tours fell during times I wasn't in the area!

text:
I love this place!! A food lovers paradise. Hungry??  Want to eat?? You will hurt yourself trying to figure out which of the dozens of places here to try. Of course, there are plenty of places to buy food to cook at home as well. Seafood, fruits, vegetables, meats, cheese, it's all here in one giant madhouse!!  
       Of course, it's always good to come at times that aren't as busy.  Craving dessert?? Termini's, Beilers, Bassets Ice Cream. For the love of God, if you weren't diabetic when you came in, you will be by the time you leave!!!  Keep in mind that while Sundays seem a little quieter, that's because all the Amish vendors aren't here!!  I wouldn't recommend missing Beilers and their amazing baked goods!!  
      If there is one downside, it's the parking. As in most of Philly, parking is an abomination!! your best bet may be to find the closest lot and park there. This way you can take your time inside without worrying about rushing out for the time limit on the street parking.

text:
The signs of a great market are as follows: local produce (and flavorful), good bazaar (and fun), and really (really) delicious food (and famous!). When there's more than 250 food dealers and countless of tempting (not so calorie-conscious), as well as few healthy choices under one roof, from Hershel's reuben, Beck's mac n' cheese fried balls, to Beiler's maple bacon doughnut, I bet you can't stop eating at just one stall. Luckily, you can always come back for more.  P.S: Don't forget your Tums

What a tourist might pick:
- DiNic's: Roast Beef and Pork. ( Winner of best sandwich in America'12)
- The Original Turkey: The Stuffin' Cranberry. ( All-year-round Thanksgiving)
- Beck's Cajun Caf: Train Wreck.

What a local might pick:
- Flying Monkey Bakery: Pumpple. (2 pies in 1: a pumpkin pie and an apple pie)
- Dutch Eating Place: Scrapple breakfast sandwich.
- The Famous 4th Street Cookie Company. ( $1 cookie holler before closing )

What I might pick:
- Meltkraft:  Valley Thunder Grilled Cheese.
- Beck's Cajun Caf: Shrimp & Chicken Gumbo. 
- Kamal's Middle Eastern Specialties: Chicken Shawarma. 
- Iovine Brothers Produce: Local fruits & vegetables. (10% discount on Wed. and Sun. for all students and Jefferson ID employees) 


Pro tips:
1/ Take your kids, they'll love Philbert the pig: Reading Terminal Market's mascot. 
2/ Get $4 parking validation with a purchase of $10: Two hours limit, and valid only for two assigned garages: 11th & Arch Streets (Expert Parking), 12th & Filbert Streets (Parkway Garage). 
3/ Amish vendors aren't at RTM on Sundays.
4/ Free WiFi access.

Five Yelps.

text:
Can't really say much that hasn't already been covered by close to 5000+ reviews other than I wish I had two or three extra stomachs just to be able to try everything. Just keep an eye on the hours since a lot of the places started shutting down when we came here in the late afternoon and maybe try not to come on the weekends if you can't stand large crowds. 

Things we tried:
1. Blueberry and apple fritters from Beiler's. Donuts usually rank a little lower than cookies for me if I'm in the mood for something carb-y and sweet but this really knocked all of our socks off. The Boston creme was way too sugary. 

2. Famous 4th Street Cookie Co. Incandescent. I took a bite and levitated a few feet off the ground. I think this even beats Levain for me. It was so unbelievable. I went back the next day for another (original chocolate chip no walnuts - and yes, they do have a version with walnuts).

3. A ginger shot from the stand selling ginger drinks. 

4. Smucker's jerky. We went there on consecutive days to pick up some more. 

Didn't get to try some of the other famous options, like DeNic's sandwich and the apple dumplings. There was also a little tea stand that looked very promising and Pearl's oyster bar. Next time!

text:
Wall-to-wall five star ratings don't intimidate me. Philadelphia's Reading Terminal Market is a logistical nightmare. Sure, the food selections are global in scope and generally delicious but seating is at a premium and movement through the clogged labyrinth of stalls and tributaries is downright dystopian. 

I have no idea who's writing these hosannas to the RTM but all I saw was a bunch of grim faced fun seekers choking on their pulled pork and cannolis while balancing on one leg in the maelstrom. 

I know that I'm in the minority here but this contrarian is absolutely not passing Go, not collecting $200 and definitely not taking another ride on the Reading Railroad.

text: This is a must see/stop by to experience! I adore the Reading Terminal Market. They have so many different things to offer thanks to all of their amazing vendors. If able to stop by, make sure to try a freshly made grilled cheese with farm fresh cheese, as well as some freshly baked donuts and whoopie pies from the local Amish people. The flying money has great cookies, and there is also a local honey/bee stand that sells great candles! There are so many other things to eat and try but those are my favorites. You will even find their infamous chocolate covered onion which is made at their local chocolate shop, Mueller Chocolate Co. This is a gag gift which visitors get a real kick out of!

text: Reading Terminal Market is a huge indoor food market in downtown Philadelphia.  There are hundreds of stalls that offer all kinds of foods from meats to fruits, vegetables and pastries.  If you are hungry this is the place for you.  There are also vendors that offer vegan and vegetarian options as well.  Tons of food to choose from.  Beware, it's crowded.  Parking is difficult as well.  There is very little street parking, however there is a city parking garage which fills up quickly.  Also don't forget to get your ticket validated at the market, otherwise parking is very expensive.  With validation 3 hrs. max for $5, otherwise your looking at about $10 an hour.  It's definitely worth going if you are hungry!

text:
As a Philly native, there's not a thing I don't like about this place, except for the crowds that seem to never disperse except at 4pm in the Amish section. Let me give you 2 of my favorite sweets places:

Beiler's is a conveniently located donut spot in the predominantly Amish section on the 12th street side closer to Arch street. My favorite donut(s) are the fritters, but particularly the blueberry one.

4th Street, the best cookie stop in the city IMO, is smack dab in front of the entrance at 12th and Filbert. These humongous cookies are sold by weight, but I pretty much always leave with at least 6 because getting to the counter is almost impossible some days. The peanut butter chocolate chip and regular chocolate chip are divine, but you can't really go wrong.

Obviously I could go on and on, but I'll let you take the adventure on your own.

text: The last time I visited Reading Terminal Market was over 10 years ago, when I was in middle school. Even at such a young age, I knew this place was special. The thing I remember most from that time was an ice cream cone that was bigger than my head at the time, but you better believe I polished off that entire thing! Now, coming back as an adult, I was able to appreciate Reading Terminal Market in all of its full glory. Over the past few years, fancy, often overpriced food halls have become more popular, but Reading Terminal Market embraced that concept years ago, and is quite reasonably priced. There are upwards of 30 vendors offering everything from meals to dessert to groceries and various Amish delicacies. It is always extremely crowded on weekends and at lunchtime on weekdays, so if you can go during off-peak times, you will have the best experience! Keep in mind that this is not a fancy restaurant, and not necessarily the cleanest, most modern interior, but the food is great and the prices can't be beat!

text: This place is the BEST place to do grocery shopping, have lunch, and bring out of town guests to. I live only a block away and my grocery bills have gone down significantly because (most of) the shops at Reading Terminal are so much cheaper and fresher than a traditional grocery store. Iovine Brothers is great for produce, and they give student discounts of 10% on Wednesday and Sundays. Wan Seafood is great for fish supply. The spice shop right next to Flying Monkey has great spices, marinades, dressings, teas, etc. Not to mention the desserts are great at almost any of the chocolate shops. The beer garden and numerous lunch places (great cheesesteaks, falafels, crab cakes, anything you could want) make this great for groups also.

text:
One of the places that I worked inside before and have grown to love over the years. I mean face it. There are so many reason why you love and hate this place at the same time.

Why you hate it - it has a bad sushi display,it has a traditional diner that isn't open 24/7 (how does this exist), it's buffet section is kind of seedy, it has a horrible bar inside, Rick's Steaks moving out is going to kind of suck, there are 3 or 4 Chinese style stands and only one of them might be traditional.

Why You love it - incredible market atmosphere overall,The best Amish farmers section that's anywhere outside of Pennsylvania Dutch territory,  plenty of Authentic multicultural cuisines for inexpensive prices, piano music on the way to the bathroom, an incredible cooking book section, one of the best cheese stands ever, the fun events that take place, and the fact that Tony Luke's should be moving in could be amazing. 

No Matter what the good of it always outweighs the bad.

text:
Reading Terminal Market is a must-see in Philly, though I found myself a bit overwhelmed by crowds and options on a weekend afternoon. I like that there are a lot of grocery vendors, like seafood, produce, and tea, and not just food stalls. The offerings lean classic and fast food-y rather than super millennial or artisanal.

Lines for Philly cheese steaks are long but move quick; I don't think this is the place to try it unless you're on a speed-tour like I was, as I thought it was pretty average and the experience getting it was stressful. The donut place is a cool stop to see them making different pastries, though I thought the one we had was meh. An unexpected highlight was the infused olive oil and vinegar spot-- you have to try everything.

I do appreciate that prices aren't overly inflated, but for me the crowds just made this too hectic. We really had to fight for seats, like looking around at multiple locations for over ten minutes. Try to hit it on a weekday if possible.

text:
The Reading Terminal Market (RTM) is a foodie haven! It's one of the most well-known indoor markets in the country, so stopping by is a must if you're in Philadelphia.

PROS:
- Multiple dining options! From Cajun dishes to homey soul food and delicious breakfast and brunch items, there is a little bit of everything for everyone.
- Moreover, there is always something new during your next visit! With all of the vendors inside, it is difficult to eat everything you see in one visit.
- $4 parking at 2 different garages for 2 hours! All you need to do is take your parking ticket, spend $10 at ONE vendor and have that place validate it for you before you return to your vehicle and pay.
- The vendors are all friendly. Smiles were abound and enticing dishes were everywhere to be found!

CONS:
- Crowded and touristy. I accidentally "shouldered" a high schooler (or middle schooler?) from out of town because of how crowded this place gets (and because he was hogging the aisle).
- The open seating area is limited. You have two options: Wait for a table to open up OR you could join one. Some vendors, like Molly Malloys, have their own seating area. My family and I were fortunate enough to grab a table after a few minutes of waiting and, seconds later, two people joined us at the table. I'm totally fine with this, but hopefully part of the ongoing construction includes additional seating areas.
- Lines, lines, lines! Everyone wants a taste of the delicious doughnuts at Beiler's or the famous Roast Pork Sandwich from DiNic's, so expect to wait awhile at the popular vendors/stalls.

All things considered, RTM is a great place to grab a bite or even shop for a few groceries! I love the idea of indoor markets and food halls, so visiting this place was a great experience. I'm looking forward to my next visit.

text: This has to be a must see on any trip to Philly.  I've been to Philly a lot in the past 3 years and I normally get there at around lunch time. There is no better place to start than reading Market. They have everything you can imagine all under one roof.  Want to try a cheese steak, there's  Spataro's Cheesesteaks.  Want what's is becoming Philly's signature sandwich, go to  DiNic's for one of their Slow cooked Italian roast pork, broccoli rabe sandwichs, with thick chunks of Sharpe provolone. You have a sweet tooth there are 7 bakeries and 4 candy booths. There is a clam bar and for those that like there lunches wet, there's Molly Malloy's. Now I'm not saying that this is all that Philly has to offer, far from it but it is worth spending at least an hour in.

text:
RTM is a philadelphia staple. You can find all types of cuisine, bakeries/coffee shops, grocery, small shops, and even a diner. Whatever you are in the mood for you can find it here. If you are lost go to their 12th and Filbert entrance and speak to the front desk staff. There are also copies of the RTM map. Take the map and explore the whole place. You can easily spend all day here just eating your way through Philadelphia. 

Keep in mind lunch hours here are insane. You have people coming here during their work lunch and then the hundreds of thousands of tourists who are in town as well. It is busy busy BUSY. Plan accordingly. 

The entire front left side of the market (the side along 12th and Arch) is closed on Mondays. Welcome to the city!

text:
Reading Terminal market has the best value for quick food in Philly.  There are so many options from grilled cheeses and cheese steaks, to ice cream and smoothies.  It is the perfect location for a large group that cannot decide on what they are in the mood for. 

The deli's make fantastic sandwiches, Meltkraft has the best grilled cheeses around, and there a handful of ice cream and fruit smoothie joints to choose from.  Not only do they have classic American food, but they have restaurants providing dishes from around the world.  Indian, German, Greek, and several Asian cuisines are all represented; just to name a few.  

The only thing that's a little tricky and can be a pain is the limited amount of seating. It is set up in a fashion with vendors down a line and winding all over the area, with the tables all clustered in the middle.  Usually there is a wait for seating, so I would advise standing if it is at all possible.  Besides this I love the variety and the option to chow down on whatever I'm in the mood for!

text: This is the first visit we make since last year.  With the new health ordinance from the city of Philadelphia, ALL seating inside the Reading Terminal has been removed so the overall feeling of the terminal is of wider space. Masks are required, around the perimeter of the terminal you have security and they have set high boy tables for people to buy food and consume the food standing up with a place to at least eat your food standing.  I an cool with that. Me traveling for the day, i was ready with a picnic basket cause thats how we New Yorkers do...(plates, paper towels and plastic utensil) as i was craving soul food. We visited a few places hadvid deli, dutch place, four seasons juice bar, kevin Parker soul food.  The bathrooms were extremely clean and well attended throughout the day.  Tables out of the building were also kept clean, as you finish your meal and your group clears the table, they sanitize the table tops quickly.  They have enough security outside that i felt comfortable to not be hassled by the homeless population.

text:
This little piggy went to market,
This little piggy definitely didn't stay home,
This little piggy had roast beef and a bunch of other crap to,
This little piggy had none (what an idiot),
And this little piggy cried wee wee wee all the way home because they were full as shit after eating non-stop for over an hour.

This place is seriously dope.  It reminds me of faneuil hall marketplace in Boston except it is a legit market with local vendors where you can get everything from produce to baked goods as opposed to just being a giant food court. I mean they have that too but at least they can legitimately call themselves a market.

My biggest advice is buy stuff from anyone who looks remotely amish.  Their baked goods are incredible.  Sticky buns and pecan pie that I had there has me salivating right now thinking about it.

Also 2 hour parking for $4 with validation from a vendor here.  Go to the website for specifics.  But how awesome is that?

Downside?  Crowded as all hell.  Be prepared to throw elbows, shoulders, and dropkicks or be really quick on your feet in order to get a table to sit at.

text:
Reading Terminal Market is an amazing place to come to and walk around.  It will be crowded, especially on the weekends, but it's worth it to come by.  They have about 20 places to eat lunch or dinner at, from cheesesteaks, to pizza, to seafood, to gyros, to Chinese food and more.

My wife loves the bakeries above all, there are fresh cookies, breads doughnuts cannoli and more.  You can also get fresh jams to put on your bread.  They have several Dutch bakeries within the market.

Definitely come stop by, it's worth it!

text: I haven't been there in a while, but it was always bustling and crowded with people looking for a delicious (but not cheap) lunch.  At the south end near the middle is a great mushrooms stand that sells Hen of the Woods.  Sautee these tiny mushroom clusters and add them to spaghetti sauce for a real treat.  The selection of cheeses in the market is enormous (most are made with animal rennet).  I'm a fan of Malone's restaurant, which is one of the few places in the market with comfortable seating.  There was a tv documentary made about the market in which they interviewed the owner, and he seemed like a good-hearted and hard working person.  Another treat in the market is chocolates, mostly on the west side.  It's a great place to spend a lively afternoon.  Go a little early or late to avoid the peak of the lunch hour.

text:
Bottom Line:  A clean market that offeres a variety of foods and a great experience. 

If you've played Monopoly you've probably heard of the Reading Railroad.  In the late 1890s the Reading Terminal was built and used as a passenger train station and train depot.  But by the 1980s the building was no longer effective as a train terminal so the site was eventually repurposed, in part for the well-liked foodie market.  

Reading Terminal Market has over 100 vendors.  Some vendors are selling prepared foods while other are selling groceries, specialty items and gifts.  Meat, seafood, cheese, vegetables, chocolate and other goodies are plentiful here.  This place is a cacophony of sights, sounds and smells.  As a first timer I enjoyed methodically weaving my way through the market checking out all of the stalls.  Unfortunately I was there on a Sunday, a day that the Amish vendors do not participate in the market.  Other than grabbing some lunch I didn't buy anything but I would love to come back to try Bassett's Ice Cream, DiNic's and Molly Malloy's.

text:
I'm still making my way through to eat from every food stand in the Market (each visit makes me wish I could eat more!), but nothing has disappointed. 

There are more than enough reviews here, so I'm keeping this short.  Try everything, or if you're a tourist and not here often, don't be afraid to try something that's not hyped--you might still find something amazing.  Let yourself wander.   It's really about the experience.

Some favorite items:
-Blueberry/apple fritters, maple bacon donuts from Beiler's-- doughy, warm, fresh, sugary goodness.
-FRESH mozzarella from Meltkraft.   I literally eat it plain with fork and knife.
-Flying Monkey's woopie pies.
-$1 closeout cookies around 5pm from Famous 4th Street [on a slow day]
-Peking duck, easily accessible without going to Chinatown.
-Apple dumplingw/ heayv cream from the amish diner (foodies--this was featured on Food Network)

text:
I love coming here to eat. If you want to navigate the market in an efficient manner, there are maps available when you enter. This place closes at 5pm, so make sure you get here early. Reading Terminal Market has everything - fresh produce, seafood, meat, cookies, coffee, omelettes, grilled cheese etc.  
There are also lots of Amish owned business here if you want to eat some Pennsylvanian Dutch food!

Here are some of my favorite spots:

Miller's Twist: get your hands on a breakfast pretzel log. I got one that was filled with bacon, cheese and egg and it was amazing. The pretzel was buttery, and the filling was warm and cheesy. I was there in the morning and there was definitely a line for these amazing breakfast logs. This spot is Amish owned too!

Sweet as Fudge Candy Shoppe: Another Amish owned business with lots of candy, and home made fudge. You can ask for samples of the fudge, which are made with real cream and butter!

Old City Coffee: Great place to grab coffee, they can also make your coffee fancy as they have a variety of syrups! They do sell coffee beans which you can take home.

Bassetts Ice Cream: This place has such amazing ice cream- I tried the strawberry which tasted like real fruit. The salted caramel pretzel was the bomb - vanilla ice with chocolate covered pretzels and caramel drizzle. This was soooo amazing.

Can't wait to come back!

text:
What do you say about an amazing place that already has over 600 reviews?  I know; put the ten (10) most important things you need to know all in one place.  So, especially if you are a 1st timer, read on.

1. Be prepared to embrace the crowds.  It's part of the Reading Terminal experience.  Think about it.  All those folks are there because the place is so amazing!

2. Don't visit on Sunday, Monday, or Tuesday.  Why you ask?  There are over a dozen Pennsylvania Dutch (Amish) vendors that are definitely worth visiting.  They have special hours and don't open on these days.  It would be a mistake not to see them.

3. If you want the very best deals make sure you end your visit during the last hour of each day.  That would be between 5:00 and 6:00 PM Monday -Saturday and 4:00 to 5:00 PM on Sunday.

4. If you are a foodie be prepared to be overwhelmed, stunned, amazed, and generally blown away.  You won't be able to do it justice in two (2) hours.  Think three (3) or more.

5. Speaking of two (2) hours, it will cost you $4 for that amount of time at the 12th & Filbert garage.  All you need to do is spend $10 and any vendor will validate your ticket.  Even better is to not park at all and take public transportation.  

6. Check the website for cool events especially to see the live music schedule.  http://www.readingterminalmarket.org/events/

7. Some folks say the place is touristy and they are partially correct.  That's true of some of the vendors but anyone with half a brain can spot them in a second.  If that's not your thing just walk on by.

8. If you want to stay in the market and have an adult libation, check out Molly Malloy's.  It's a great place for a beer.

9. If you are thinking about lunch at prime time (11:30-1:00), please think again.  And then think again and again.  Trust me; it's complete and utter craziness.  Eat early or eat late.

10. Last but not least let's talk Tommy DiNic's as this legendary emporium deserves special mention.  I know, I know, you saw Man vs. Food and you want "The Sandwich."  Is it worth it?  Yeah, it is.  Stroll the market and stop back occasionally to check on the length of the line.  If you see it below twenty five (25) folks, go for it.  It really is an amazing sandwich.

As just about everyone says this place is a must for a Philly visitor.

text: This is the market to which all other public markets should be judged. Whether you're shopping for food or looking for a meal this is the spot. It's a total mix of cultures from South Philly guys selling cheesesteaks, to the Asian seafood market, to the Southern Soul Food, to the Amish vendors, and everything in between. The oldest business in the market (and one of the oldest in all of Philly) is Bassett's Ice Cream (in Philly since 1861) they make some of the creamiest ice cream around. Two of my favorite treats here are the Amish pretzels at Miller's Twists and the Apple Dumplings at Dutch Eating Place (just to name a couple). The Terminal Market is a huge clean place and there's always a seat or two to sit and relax or eat, one seating area even has a piano player playing throughout the day. If food isn't your thing there are also a couple shops selling spices, wines, and gifts. If I had to narrow it down I would have to say Reading Terminal is one of the top 3 things to do while in Philly (next to the Art Museum and Eastern State Penn).

text:
Based on selection and quality of food alone, I'd rate this place as close to a 5 as it can get without jumping in front of me during the climactic gun fight with Lo Pan and the Decepticons.

In terms of actual experience going there, I'd rate it a 3.5, if I'm being generous.

This all averages out to a solid 4.

The only reason the experience can be kind of stressful is that it's always packed. Like, Asian night market packed. Like, gambling den on 4 v 4 cockfight night packed. You get the picture. Whether you just want a container of takeaway, or some quality meats, cheese, or artisan whatever, you will be waiting in line, likely for 15-20 minutes. I've yet to come here at a time of day when it wasn't filled up like 25 cent drink night at Paddy McRegretfuls.

That said, you have to go here, and you have to try everything. They have what you like, I guarantee it - except Vietnamese cuisine, I haven't seen that there.

text:
Where do I even begin. This place is massive and packed. Brace yourself as you walk through the doors. 

The market has a lot to offer so you can grab a map when you walk in or wander and see where the road takes you. We stopped and tried a few stands as we were visiting and wanted to try everything. There's a polish stand inside that offered amazing head cheese. It's towards the 'picnic area' seating. I ordered a pork chop from this vendor as well. Delicious!

Make sure to try all the Dutch goods available. It's out of this world, the jerky vendor has some of the best jerky I've had in a while.

All in all, I loved it. Hopefully next time I stop by I won't be packed in like a sardine.

text:
I have found a cure for claustrophobia. Reading Terminal Market. Crowded and bustling but everywhere you look there is something new to see and you are assaulted by mouth watering smells and temptations every few paces. It makes the volume of people jostling you entirely bearable.

My fave samplings:
Termini Brothers for tasty cheese cannoli, fig bars, sfogliatelle, pignoli cookies and biscotti.
Fisher's for Amish pretzels with butter
Lancaster Co Dairy for fresh squeezed lemonade
Salumeria for gourmet meats and cheese which made for an awesome midnight snack
Dutch Eating Place for food that is similar to Grandma's and a kick ass apple dumpling.

If I lived in Philly I would be in here all the time, the shopping looked incredible, super fresh products of all sorts. So sad to miss DiNic's though, I will have to return at some point. Thanks to Bobby P, Andrew T and Mira V for the suggestion.

text:
Stopped in Philadelphia for a quick weekend trip and ended up at Tony Luke's right before we headed to the airport. I need to preface this review by stating, I'm not a Philadelphia cheese steak pro. I normally order they in Miami with onions, peppers, mushrooms and I find that to be quite tasty but is it an authentic Philly cheese steak? I don't know. 

Anyway, we arrived here Sunday afternoon. It was pretty busy but the line moved quickly. We ordered four cheese steaks with provolone cheese. I messed up and forgot to order fries. I was pretty bummed about that, they looked delicious. 10 minutes later they called our name and we were all really excited to dig in and it was just... ok. The sandwiches were kinda cold and I thought they were dry as well. I didn't think it was anything to write home about. I actually only ate half of my sandwich and when I arrived home that night, I added some mayo and warmed it up in the microwave and it was a lot better. 

I didn't try any of the other places listed online as the best in the area and next time I go to PHL I'll make sure to check it out. Locals, please feel free to give me your suggestions! What did I do wrong? Is it supposed to be just simple meat and cheese?

text:
What the hell have I been doing?  Going to Pat's and Geno's for cheesesteak?  They've got nothing on Tony Luke's!  Not only is Tony Luke's easier to find, they have their own parking lot under the I-95.  That and their cheesesteak is frakkin' good.  You know the place is legit when there are more locals than tourists on the line.

My wife and I split two sandwiches.  The first one up was a cheesesteak with sweet peppers, onions, and cheese wiz.  The beef was so tender and juicy.  The bread had a slight crunchiness to it but still soft on the inside.  Next up was the roast pork Italian with sharp provolone and broccoli rabe.  That was really good too but I will go with the mild provolone next time.

This is the best cheesesteak I've ever had.  Take it from a guy who has driven to Philly a couples of times just for cheesesteak.

text:
Even before the plane landed in our first trip to Philadelphia, we knew that the first thing to do was to get our hands on some chessesteaks and not our hotel. 

This iconic south Philly dive is a lot smaller than seen on TV, but thankfully the portions were not. There is a small parking area behind a lottery shack and the line full of locals/tourists clearly speaks for its popularity. The menu is extensive posted on the aluminum siding and you can watch the cooks create their craft. The picnic dining area with a condiment section is small. There is a 10-15 minute wait before they call out your name with a black bag in hand. Cash for sure and credit cards seemed to be accepted. Maybe I had really high expectations, but I felt cheesesteaks were over-rated and the roast pork was definitely tasty. 

What we ordered:
- cheesesteak with cheese wiz
- roast pork with sharp provolone - recommend 
- fried onion rings

When we went:
- Thursday @ 1:00 PM 

Would we return:
- next time, I'll get the onions on the steaks or try their hoagies.

text:
This was my second Italian Roast Pork Sandwich in the span of three days, and it was infinitely better than the first from DiNic's.  Absolutely amazing. Seriously.

One sultry Monday afternoon, I had to pick up a package from the UPS on Oregon Avenue.  I live in West Philadelphia, and it's extremely difficult to get to South Philly from West Philly using public transportation so I asked my friend to drive me there, on the condition that I buy her a something to eat.  On the way there, we spotted Tony Luke's and considered eating there after getting my package. We spent the longest time in an unairconditioned, crowded, totally inefficient UPS, and the last thing I wanted in 100 degree weather was a hot sandwich.  But the foodspotting app on my phone was completely overtaken by photos of Tony Luke's sandwiches, so I had little choice but to give in.  

Since we decided to split a sandwich so we had to agree on which one to order.  I was so disappointed by my first roast pork sandwich, and I had just had it two days ago, so I was rooting for the veal cutlet.  My friend desperately wanted roast pork, and I asked a guy in front of us (I got the feeling he knew what he was doing) what he recommended, and he had tried everything (I was right) and loved the roast pork.  We received our food pretty quickly, even though not right when we ordered it like at Pat's and Geno's.  Tony Luke's didn't seem to have the same assembly line operation as those two, which gives me more of the feeling that the sandwiches are ~made with love~.  But that's probably just me...

But anyways, Tony Luke's completely redeemed the roast pork sandwich in my mind.  With that single first bite, any previous notions of roast pork as unimpressive, not flavorful, and dry quickly vanished.  For about $9, we ordered the roast pork sandwich with broccoli rabe and sharp provolone (the same exact thing I ordered at DiNic's) and I almost put hot peppers on it, thinking I had learned from my last experience.  But this time, it didn't need anything.  The sandwich was divine.  So juicy, so much flavor, the broccoli rabe was not bitter and the sharp provolone was slighly melted and not overpowering at all.  I was told by the guy in front of me that the roast pork was spicy, which it wasn't really, but it did have a little kick and my mouth felt a little bit tingly from it.  It was so unbelievably delicious, and not just because my first roast pork sandwich was bad...that just required the Tony Luke's sandwich to be extraordinary to make up for it.  And it certainly did.

It's really hard to make it out to Tony Luke's without a car, but I hope I can return.  It's definitely worth the trip.

text:
So sad:  Last time I was here, this place was located across the street. It had all your basic amenities, like comfortable seating, table service, ac, restrooms and if memory serves, even a bar. 

Flash forward to our latest visit:  We pull into the parking lot of the new (ish) location and spot a trio of porta potties.  "Must be for construction workers, " I reassure myself.  Alas, no.  This spot is BARE BONES.   Not only are there no "normal" restrooms, it is counter service only, with just a few random tables with bench (read: no back support) seating.  On the sweltering day we visited, there was also no ac.  Not the best way to begin, and honestly, had we known ahead of time, we would not have eaten here. The Tony Luke's we remembered had a casual, but comfortable ambience that we were looking forward to for a relaxing dinner.  This place...Not so much.

At any rate, on to the sandwiches.  Kid and I both got the classic Cheesesteak with American and Fried Onions.   Meat was nice and tender, but a little bland to me.  In hindsight, I should have added roasted long, hot peppers, an option for extra $ on the menu.  Afterward, I noticed a little condiments stand that included hot cherry peppers, but they were whole, making them awkward to eat in a sandwich. Hubby got the Roasted Pork with Provolone and Broccoli Rabe.  Since he had bad flashbacks of eating and hating pungent melted sharp provolone the last time we were here, he swapped it out for a mild version of the cheese.  I don't think it came even close to the South Philly-inspired Roast Pork sandwich from Federoff's in Brooklyn, but it hit the spot.  

Ultimately, I am a girl who needs an indoor restroom when I go out to dinner.  Call me a princess, but there it is.  Next time we're in Phiilly, we will go someplace else.

name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
I've only been once, but the experience was beyond anything I could have hoped for.

The Background:  En route from San Francisco to Montreal for a bachelor party.  The bachelor and one of the other travel companions when to school in Philly and suggested we head for a cheesesteak during our three hour layover at PHI.  We landed at 6am and were at Tony Luke's by 6:30.

The Experience:  We go up to the window and three of us order cheesesteaks and the other orders the pork italian.  Bad news, too early for the pork italian and it is going to be a 45 minute wait.  4th decides to go for cheesesteak.  All are satisfied.

Four cheesesteaks consumed, the 4th goes back to order the pork italian.  The four of us split the second round.  Even more satisfied.

Back to the airport:  OK, so taking a cab to Tony Luke's probably isn't the best idea we've ever had.  We call the a cab company and wait... and wait... and see a UPS guy steal cash from a purse sitting next to an electrified sign... and wait... and wait... and see a homeless guy we appropriately named Cheeseus.... and wait.  Finnaly the cab shows up and we take the 2nd leg of the flight to Burlington, VT (hitting up the local Hooters) and drove to Montreal.

Best part of the entire trip with probably Tony Luke's!

text: While visiting Philly over the fourth of July holiday, I found Tony Luke's using my Yelp app. It was truly meant to be as the delicious cheesesteak hoagie I had made a lasting impression on me. I devoured the cheesesteak hoagie and it's melting provolone cheese as if we had known each other all our lives. There is parking on the street as well as adjacent to the building under the underpass. Limited seating but there is room to stand at the counter and enjoy your purchase. There are t-shirts available if you really want a memento of your experience. Even though I was a newbie, the cashier didn't rush me and was very nice. They do accept credit cards and will call your name when your order is ready. Be prepared to call a tow truck to move you when you've finished as these sandwiches are so satisfying.

text:
The moment I bit into my first sandwich from Tony Luke's, I heard a distant strain of "Philadelphia Freedom" fill my ears, and I felt the foundations of my mid-Atlantic culinary knowledge begin to shake. A couple of bites later, they were lying crumbled at my feet, victims of popular knowledge and misinformation. Oh, how wrong I was! Wrong, wrong, wrong! 

For instance: the meat on a cheesesteak does NOT need to include bits of gristle and fat. It can be lean, meltingly tender and packed with flavor. It can also include roast pork in addition to beef: I don't really even like pork, but this was so delicious I think I'd have to do some soul-searching before placing my next steak order.

Or: the idea that cheesesteaks must include plastic cheese to be authentic. In my former ignorance I held to this heresy, but at Tony Luke's I was peer-pressured into ordering sharp provolone instead, and the sandwich came full of melty, creamy goodness, but without any of the petroleum-byproduct tinniness from the can -- just biting, pungent cheese flavor in blistered bubbles of perfection.

And that other pesky ideal, that cheesesteaks are best enjoyed plain? Only true if the add-ons are as mediocre as they usually are. Here, you can get the requisite fried onions, which lend a smoky flavor to the sandwich, but you can also order broccoli rabe, which has been stewed to remove any bitterness and adds a juicy, fresh depth. Oh, my, it was delicious. 

The one thing I remain convinced of is that the bread makes the sandwich. In this case, it's delivered fresh each day; my Philly source says the other Tony Luke's locations receive par-baked loaves and finish them onsite, but the result is less than stellar. This bread was a classic French baguette: chewy outside, fluffy inside, a meal in itself or a spectacular case for the tender meat and melting cheese of a perfect lunch.

text:
A cheesesteak place that has a vegetarian sandwich f-in rocks, well for me!  You're probably saying, how is a vegetarian gonna review a cheesesteak place - blah, blah, blah.  Well, I wasn't always a vegetarian, and I've eaten at Geno's, Jim's and Pat's - and all the typical tourist spots.  

Tony Luke's has got the best stuff around.  I've eaten here a ton of times for lunch with guys who know Philly and know their food. I get the same thing all the time - Uncle Mike's - which is broccoli rabe, spinach, fried onions, sharp provolone, long hots, sweet peppers, and tiny bit of tomato sauce (mixed into all that goodness) on their freshly baked bread.  The guys mix it up, they order cheesesteaks, roast pork with rabe and sharp prov, hot roast beef, or chicken cutlet with rabe and sharp provolone.  You can't beat it!

If you're not from Philly, please don't take the personalities at the counter to heart, they mean well, there's just a long line and they're really not trying to make new friends.  It's cool, your sandwich will come out just fine.

text:
In my ongoing mission to hit as many of the joints I see on TeeVee and in the rags, I welcomed my first real trip to Philly. I had hit DiNics at noon (see my review here at Yelp), gone and did the Clinic I was in town to do, and now, It was time for dinner. At the Enterprise Rentacar desk at the Airport, the Gent there advised only the tourists went to Geno's or Pat's for Cheesesteaks. Locals go to Tony Lukes.
But I couldn't visit Philly and not at least TRY to go to that famous corner, which is smack dab in the middle of a claustrophobic residential neighborhood. Nowhere to park, and lines at both places like those you find at Disneyland. I wanted to grab a picture, but the traffic was so dense, I couldn't even do that. Rats!
So Tony Luke's it was!
There are a few Tony Luke's in town, but I'm all about OldSchool, so only the original would do. In an industrial part of town which has prolly seen better days, I kluged a parking spot (i was driving a hot black gorgeous brand-new Chrysler 300c) adjacent to TL's, under the freeway, with a few unsavory-looking Youths nearby. Maybe I shoulda swung with a safer location, but it was getting late. I would tough it out. There was a modest line, and the pic-a-nic tables were jammed. This wadn't a-gonna be easy! I did do a little reconnoiter as how to order at TL's. and for me it was a Cheesesteak whiz wit'. I also called an audible when I saw "Italian Pork with Broccoli Rabe and Provolone" on the Menu. I took my two torpedo-sized Sarnies to a table that had miraculously cleared as I approached. (the Philly Food Gods must have been on my side, as the same thing happened earlier that day at DiNics!) As I sat down, a funky and zaftig young gal moseyed over with her own torpedo. "Mind if I sit with you?" to which I answered "Sure!". She sat down and tore into her Cheesesteak with lusty abandon. This was going to be fun! I pounced upon my cheesesteak, and it was tasty indeed. Kinda sloppy-this is not something I'd want to eat in the Chrysler. 
All-in-all the Cheesesteak wasn't neck-and-neck with the DiNic's sarnie I scarfed earlier in the day. If I hadn't gone to DeNic's I would be jumping up and down over the TonyLuke's Cheesesteak, but it was kinda like an Italian Beef without the Giardinera. The Gal across the table identified herself as the Former Culinary director of Barnum and Bailey's Circus. She certainly knew how to eat. I et half of my Cheesestaek and turned my attention to TonyLuke's Roast Pork.
Jumping Jesus-This sarnie blew away DiNics! Great garlic note, tangy greens, and an explosion of Flavor. This was the ber-Philly experience I had been waiting for.
The Circus gal said that Tony Luke's was far and away the top dog in town for these sarnies, I had to agree. I dispatched the entire thing, waddled back to the Chrysler, bidding Circus Gal adieu. I was stuffed like a Christmas goose...
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
There are so many things wrong with this place, I don't even know where to begin. I guess I'll start with the worst, and go from there.

The customer service is probably the worst I have ever experienced.  We walked up to the window and the lady stared blankly in front of her like she didn't see us.  That's what I thought, until I realized she just had a horrible attitude and wasn't going to acknowledge us until we started to order.  Similar rudeness occurred throughout the entire experience.  It boggles my mind that the Tony Luke's establishment thinks this woman's attitude is an acceptable attitude for one of their employees to have, much less one who is working in a customer service role.  

The food is common street food that you can get anywhere in Philly.  Please, do not drive down to south Philly and wait in a hour line for some regular ass Philly food.  There wasn't much of a line when went there, so we figured we'd check it out.  I ordered a fish sandwich with pickles and lettuce.  The menu said it came with tartar sauce, but my sandwich had none on it.  It came on a huge, very hard hoagie roll. Why? No one wants a fish hoagie.  Also, the fish pieces were pretty small and cheap, kind of like something you'd get from the freezer section of the grocery store.  I ate the fish and threw the bread away. It was utterly disappointing.

My boyfriend got a chicken cheesesteak, which was also nothing spectacular.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
I'm a foodie, I admit it - so anytime there's something as talked about as say a cheesesteak from philly; I'm eventually going to go try it. I may or may not be disappointed. 

In this case, the first time I went I was immediately a fan. I've NEVER had a bad cheesesteak at Tony Lukes; ever. What backs up the palatte pleasure is the sheer craziness of the atmosphere. You park in the middle of the street (more fun if you show up on say a Saturday in the middle of the night when the 'crazies' are out); order a delicious sandwich without fear of 'screwing up' like you do at Pats, you grab a seat in the very clean and appointed seating area and sometimes you even get to see Ben Franklin. No joke. You meet all kinds of people, it's fun. 

Recently we went a little crazy and visited Pats, Genos and Tony Lukes all in one day (hey we were there for a hockey game, why not...you gotta eat right?). Location wise Tony Lukes wins, food quality yup, Tony Lukes again, and definitely Tony Lukes for customer service and overall experience. 

I enjoyed my provolone/wit at Pats but the bread was a little dry and thick, nothing wrong with that....but then again I can bake bread at home so I'd prefer a little less when I'm after a cheesesteak. The location is totally sketchy but because you have so many tourists going to Pats and Genos it's a little less intimidating...well; in a philly the city of not-brotherly love kind of way. 

Genos - fugheddaboudit; yuck. All I have to say. The food, the customer service (or lack thereof) and the experience. Never again...but now I can speak from experience instead of theory and hearsay. 

Tony Lukes wins my love hands down - cheesesteak with spinach rabe and provolone anyday baby. I'm in.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
Folks, if you go to Tony Lukes' get what they're known for: their Italiano style sandwiches - Roast Pork / Roast Beef or Cheesesteak ITALIANO. If you get a Cheesesteak with "whiz", then you're wasting your time and their good ribeye meat.

"Whiz" is the salty cheap-ass stuff street vendors put on steaks because it's super-cheap and doesn't take up space or require refrigeration. So a whiz steak at TL's will taste like the same whiz steak at Pat's, Geno's, Jim's or Abner's. Nothing special, you could have stayed home and poured Kraft Mac & Cheese sauce over some Dinty Moore stew instead. Or you could go to Le Bec Fin and order instant oatmeal.

Get what TL's does best: Italiano style sandwiches with broccoli rabe and sharp provolone... Even better, get the roast pork or roast beef, since they have a nice lightly peppery & garlicky au jus that soaks the bread and makes it messy and delicious.

Whiz is for tourists and people who don't know better... Just forget it even exists.

Yes, you'll wait in line to order & pick up... Yes, you'll pay cash (c'mon, it's a Cheesesteak stand!)... Yes, you may have trouble getting a seat. Oh, well, such is life sometimes. Get the ITALIANO sandwiches, and you'll see it was worth it.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping

text: I believed the hype, and it was over-hyped. First the good: the roll they use for their steaks is very tasty...crusty on the outside, soft inside. The not-so-good: I ordered the "Plain Steak." I figure if a steak place is good, their basic version should stand up. A "Plain Steak" here is just that, steak on a roll. Quality beef, but pretty bland. I had to shake on some salt to make it taste like anything. I've never been to a steak place where the basic steak didn't at least include some grilled onions in the mix. Word up, Tony: onions add FLAVOR. One other thing: a fountain soda that costs $2 should include at least one free refill. You shouldn't be charged an additional dollar for a nickel's worth of soda. It's obvious to me that Tony Luke's is coasting on it's name recognition. There are a lot of better steaks to be had in Philly.

text:
Been to Jim's, Pat's, Geno's and more . . 
Finally, got to Tony Luke's.  The line was not massive but truth be told I thought it would move faster.  It didn't.  Truth be told I thought my food would be out faster too, it wasn't.
Got the Roast Pork, Broccoli rabe and stinky provolone.  Sandwich was very good, first try of Philly style Italian Pork Sandwich.  Next time I would leave off the extra stinky provolone, it overpowered everything and didn't get "melty" at all.  I had about half the sandwich then took off the cheese.  
At that point I reconstructed the sandwich too because they put the broccoli rabe on so that it all ended up in the fold, and was pretty much impossible to get some with each bite.
Minor quibbles I know, but for these reasons not a 5 star experience for me.

Others had the Cheese Steak Hoagie (L,T,Whiz)  which was good, especially if you like larger slices of meat with almost, dare I say, a bit of chew.
The chicken parm sandwiches smelled and looked great as well.

Would of course glady go back for more.
Note on the fries, got curly fries and they were a disappointment.  Next time would get regular cut as they looked infinitely better.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
Pseudo silence.  
When two guys eat, that's the best compliment that you can give the chef.  It's the sign that the men are focusing on the food, and how good it tastes and not on other things, like girls, sports, or technology. Tony Luke's was good, but not enough to deserve an "absolute silence" status.

For me, growing up in philly, I have been craving a philly cheese steak
since the last time I visited.  Tony Luke's hit the spot, however,
I'm surprised at the over 75 ratings of 5 stars. Yes it's delishious,
but it's not great.  Like all authentic philly places, cheese steaks come with cheese wiz.  I thought the "wiz" started solidifying halfway through my sandwich, and that there was not enough meat.

Oh, and check out my pix, a dude took the 5 lb cheesesteak sandwich challenge (eat within an hour and you get it for free, plus a picture on the "hall of fame".  That is a monster of a cheesesteak.

Overall, I would give this cheesesteak a 7/10.  If you have options,
check out either: abners, jim's, or chinks (yes I'm asian and i find that name funny).

As always, check out my pix at http://picasaweb.google.com/shuilaba
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping

text:

There aren't many choices in South Philly besides Wendys, McD's, and the sandwich carts. I always leave a little disappointed. This place gets such high recommendations but my sandwich is always a little skimpy and there isn't much cheese for being a cheese steak. I have to admit the roll is perfect for the sandwich but if one were to make this at home there would be a little more to it. For the money it seems wanting.
  Next time I will try the pork with the sharp prov and broc rabe. I will check out some of the other places recommended on here as well.

text:
Yes, Tony Luke's gets the coveted 1st place award for our favorite cheesesteak in Philly.   This was our last stop of the weekend of sampling cheesesteaks.   It's actually not 'sampling' since we did manage to eat a whole cheesesteak at each of the places we visited.

The benefits of eating at Tony Luke's include:  ample parking, indoor seating, and friendly staff.   The reason for the #1 spot is that their meat was tender, the 'wiz' was plentiful and really complimented the sandwich.  I'd prefer a dryer 'bread' but the wiz and the meat really came out on the bread.   The size of the sandwich appeared to be much larger than our previous dining experiences.

I bumped it up a notch and added mushrooms and just a tiny portion of onions.   The wiz was perfect on this sammie.   Since this was 'breakfast', I stuffed myself with about half of this tube of goodness before we ventured back into the car for the 2.5 hour drive home.   When we got home, I kid you not, the sandwich was still hot.   The meat was very tender and I really like the thin slices versus the chopped up meat at other places.

text:
So the gang got together and decided to run up to Philly for the day to enjoy the weather, and we had to stop in at the cheesesteak landmarks.

First stop was Tony Luke's because one of gang was not into beef.

After about half an hour waiting in line we ordered a chicksteak, a cheesesteak, wiz wit, along with some frank fries.

I admit I stumbled with my order but the guy at the window was patient and helped me along.

We got our order within a few minutes, and it was enjoyable and there was nothing to complain about. Better than steak'um by far, and definitely better than any of the cheesesteaks in Virginia. The frank fries were a bit salty if the hot dog slivers had been chicken I think it would have been enjoyable.

Then it was off to Pat's and Geno.

Pat's and Geno was an assembly line of cheesesteaks ready to feed the masses.

Pat's was chopped up ribeye like I was used to and by far had the healthiest portion of beef. Geno's was lacking in the portions department.

For lack of speed Luke's loses out to Pat's, but beats Geno, whose cheesesteak was not living up to its hype, not to mention Luke's has an actual menu so it gets 5 stars instead of 4.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
Finally had me a phiily cheesesteak.  Got into town to visit my bro and we had Tony Lukes and it is just great.  Beef on a bun indeed, but done the way it should be....that is its good.  Went to Genos later and my girl was upset that we got "ripped off" after so many food network pump and chumps of the place.  Yeah, Geno's sucked.  I have to admit it and I'm a cheesesteak killer.   www.bestcheesesteaks.com is my favorite site.  Didn't bother going to Pats.

Ate Cheesesteak hoagie that was loaded with thinly shaved rib eye.  Tossed on some hot pepppers and I was in food shock heaven.....curly fries were just ok and coke is coke.  Bon apetit!
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping

text:
Before my sister had to leave for her flight back to California, we decided to have a late lunch eating a Philly Cheesesteak. Geno's was out of the question, since I didn't want to take her to a touristy place and deal with the street parking. I also wanted to have easy access to take the 95 to the airport.
We passed Luke's to head to John's on Snyder, but found it closed (huh?). Before contemplating the Geno route, we instead turned the car around to try this place out. The establishment was an elongated food stand with picnic style tables, a roof and a long line accompanying it. Luckily for us, the line didn't end up being outside where the fiery sun and sweltering heat was more apparent. As we sat down and unwrapped our cheesesteaks, we found really unappealing looking sliced torpedoes with slabs of beef topped with cheese (I had the whiz and she had the provolone) and grilled onions. We were hesitant to eat them at first, but with hunger lingering inside of our stomachs, we went ahead and started consuming what would eventually be one of the best cheesesteaks in Philadelphia. Not only were the cheesesteaks delicious, but their hours of operation are convenient (They're open from 6am-2am on Fridays and Saturdays!)! I also noticed that they keep their dining area clean, including the condiment station! I'd love to give them five stars, but I'd have to complain about their archaic one-at-a-time ordering system. They should figure out a way to open up another window for ordering, to reduce the annoying long line!
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping

text:
"Let's leave the game early, head to Tony Luke's and beat the crowd."

Delicious. A little messy but when every bite is heavenly, you don't really notice that you're elbow deep in whiz and mushrooms. I like to load up on pickles and let my bread soak up the juice. Oh man, my mouth is watering as I type this. I need to be reunited with the most scrumptious cheesesteak in all of Philly.

Their breakfast sandwiches are bomb too. They load up a long roll with what seems like a million eggs. I order mine with ham, mushrooms, spinach and cheese. I hit a wall half way through but plow through till the end. You can't reheat eggs and no one in their right mind would through away such a perfect sammie!

text: Tony Luke's is the place to get the world famous Philly cheesesteak.  It looks like a junky road side stand but the food is amazing.  They have a full sandwich menu but everyone lines up to order a custom steak sandwich.  You can choose from 10 kinds of cheese and add toppings like onions, peppers or mushrooms.  They have bottled or fountain drinks.  Don't forget to order some fries or deep fried onion rings.  Around the corner you can get condiments including ketchup, sour dill pickle slices and hot cherry peppers.  Grab a seat if there is one, eat in your car or rush to work or home.  It doesn't matter because all orders are bagged to go.   "When in Philly, have a cheesesteak" at Tony Luke's.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping

Short and sweet (very sweet): I got an american without (steak, american cheese,  no onions) the steak itself was seasoned and tasty and the cheese was melted (YUM)

As a side i decided to try the sweet potato fries. 1 Word... GLORIOUS. They were covered in what seemed to be maple syrup, cinnamon (possibly), and powdered sugar. They were what i expect heaven to be like (to bad im going to hell... amiright?)

Steaks are about 9$ and absolutely worth it.

Best cheesesteak ive had so far.

Only downfall we had is they labeled our steaks wrong. One has onions and the other did not (they labeled the opposite) so just double check!

text:

Ok so all the bad upfront right?  This is a landmark shop.  If you want a piece of genuine Philly from the foundation up, this is your joint.  I got two sandwiches, the cheese steak and the Italian.  Both were killer.  While it seemed like most people were trying their specialty sandwiches I don't think you can go wrong with the classics.  

Also, they had fries with sugar/cinnamon on them if you're into that kind of thing.  Not for me but salty and sweet is usually a great combination.

text:
Tony Luke's... where do I begin?

Roast Pork Italiano - be prepared to lick the wrapper once there's no sandwich left.  That goes for almost everything they make there.  

However... the one thing I don't like about Tony Luke's (now) is the nasty attitude you get from the cashier.  It's usually the same lady and she's the meanest!  We ordered the usual one night and decided to get some onion rings as well (which of course are awesome).  When we grabbed our sandwiches, they forgot the onion rings and we went back up to get them.  Cashier said, "Gimme the receipt and your bag."  She then investigatively searched our bag, threw it back to us and slammed down an order of onion rings.  All I could think of was, "Holy shit, this lady just bitched me up.  What a crazy ass!"  But maybe that's me and maybe that's just how it is at Tony Luke's.  Is it a trademark attitude they have there?  Like, is that what makes "Tony Luke's" and I'm too blind to see? Who knows but I'll keep going because it's good.

Remember when they had pictures and autographs all over the walls of the celebrities that visited?  Did they completely get rid of them or are they in the sports bar across the way?

BTW - 4 stars because Delassandro's will always rule the cheese steak race in the city.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping

I thought the pork was flavorful, but just a little bit dry. The broccoli rabe was tender and salty, and the provolone was nice and sharp. All in all a good sandwich. I'll probably try the sandwich again if I end up back in Philly, just to see if my dry pork was just a fluke.

I also got a chicken with provolone and it was chunks of chicken. Good quality ingredients and taste ok. It also wasn't greasy (juicy) which I was craving when I order a cheese steak. Total for two came out to be ~$17. 

The dining area was a bit too warm after the extremely hot temperature of past few days, so recommend taking it to go vs eating it there. Free pickle bar around the condiments area. 

Took about 15 min to get my sandwiches. This is a popular spot!
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
3.5 Stars. 

I'd first heard of this place from Tony Bruno on ESPN Radio. After hearing all his comments about the broccoli rabe and reading all the reviews, I was primed to eat here.

They actually have two Tony Luke's, one's a sit outside/order at a window type deal and the other is what looks like a sit down restaurant across the street. I came around noon and ordered from the sidewalk/order at the window joint. 

I got the roast pork italian, which has sharp provolone and your choice of spinach or broccoli rabe(I got the rabe). I also got an order of fries.  The sandwich came out relatively fast along with the fries. There was a mixup on my soda, but I got it, so no harm no foul.  I sat down at one of the aluminium tables next to the order window with my sandwich. The roast pork sandwich was so so good. The combination of the provolone and the broccoli rabe really complimented the tender pork slices.  My mouth is starting to water again just reading about it. The fries were not too bad and there were plenty of them. I"m not sure whether they were breaded or it was the potatoes they used, but it seemed a little different.  Next time I think I'll get the onion rings. 

I did have one beef with Tony Luke's. I wasn't happy however with the cleanliness of the eating area and on top of that there were multiple flies buzzing around. I know that you can't completely wipe out mother nature, but I can't help but think if they'd cleaned the place and took out the garbage more often that maybe there wouldn't have been so many flies.

Overall I enjoyed the food. I'll come back and take the sandwiches back home.

Oh yeah, there is plenty of parking next to the building.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text: Never having a real Philly Cheesesteak, I had to try Tony Luke's to see what everyone was talking about. The bread was great and crunchy, but the whiz oh my goodness! The whiz was so good, but it was a little overwhelming (I'm okay with that). I have to say I am a chopped girl, so I was disappointed in the sliced rib eye. Overall, it was a decent cheesesteak, but there are other local places where you can find one just as good if not better.

text: I've been going here for years.  I haven't tried a ton of things on the menu... I pretty much stick to the roast pork, sometimes with greens, sometimes without, but always with extra sharp.  I've also had the chicken parm sandwich on occasion.  Both are delicious!  Or if I'm in the mood for a cheesesteak, this is my go-to spot.  Forget Geno's and Pat's.  They're just tourist traps and their cheesesteaks are average.

text:
My business associate and I have spent a few jam-packed days meeting with clients and working on presentations during this week in Philadelphia, and he promised me a break from all of the work with a driving tour of the city and a stop at one of his favorite places to eat. So we bundled up against the cold weather and criss-crossed through various neighborhoods as he told me the history of Philadelphia, and shared some stories about growing up in the Italian neighborhoods of South Philly.

During our journey we drove past both Pat's and Geno's, and no telling how many other famous emporiums of cheesesteak goodness as we cruised along the major thoroughfares. Finally he parks the car on a side street, under the highway, and we march around the corner to find ourselves standing in front of the original location of Tony Luke's. Now Frank has not led me wrong all week with his recommendations for places to eat, so I was certainly psyched to try a real Philly cheesesteak.

I was freezing my niblets off in the very cold weather (after all I'm from Florida, and this frozen tundra crap is someone else's idea of fun), but sure enough we stood in line - OUTSIDE - while waiting for our turn to place our order. The menu is pretty straight forward... you have roast beef, roast pork, veal cutlet, chicken cutlet, chicken steak or rib-eye sandwiches along with a couple of other options for vegetarians and seafood lovers. At Frank's urging I ordered a Roast Beef Italian with Provolone and grilled onions and a side of onion rings.

HOLY WOW!!!! I'm not the kind of guy to say that one South Philly cheesesteak is better than another, and then have some sort of fight-to-the-death over bragging rights. I'm just going to say that this food was awesome -- tender, tasty, and flat out amazing.

Yeah, it's touristy and gimmicky, but when the food tastes this good I'm not going to complain.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text: This \review is from July 2009. I was at Penn's Landing in Philly with the family to see the Irish Naval Vessel docked there. After our tour I decided to stop at Tony Lukes on the way home-about 20 miles. As mentioned by another reviewer its basically a roadside stand with tables-but you can sit down and eat. There are round peppers and pickles by the table so you can grab as much as you want. The menu is huge but I've never eaten anything but their cheesesteaks or roast pork. A friend raves over the breakfast sandwich but I'll try that another time. Although I think the cheesesteaks are great, I can get great cheesesteaks at other places I go to. Not so with roast park. So we all got roast pork with provolone cheese and spinach rabe(wife likes the broccli rabe better). Man they were so good it almost leaves you speechless! Tender, juicy, full of flavor and a great roll. I keep thinking I'll try another item from their menu but always end up ordering the same.

text: This blows away any cheesesteak place in the area (minus Campos). The key to a great CS is the bread. Here, the bread is crispy on the outside and soft on the inside. You don't have to worry about the CS falling apart. I have tried all different types of CS here along with the por w/broccoli rabe and prov. It was very good but not outstanding like their CS. Their Texas Hot sandwich (hotdog) was unreal and I live in the hotdog capital of the NE. Stay away from Pat's/Geno's/Jims and go here. Be prepared to wait (like anywhere else) and find a seat and claim it ASAP because they are a premium. Place rocks!

text: A couple buddies and I decided to do an 8-stop cheesesteak crawl.  Tony Luke's was the first stop and boy did it set the tone!  The first thing that struck me was how great the bread was.  Flavorful with just the right amount of chew and pull nicely accompanied the rest of the cheesesteak...with fried onions, melted provolone cheese, blended nicely.    A 60/40 ratio of meat/cheese/onions to the bread was terrific.  Only thing keeping this from a fifth star...season the meat a bit more, please.  No matter, still an awesome stop, ranking #2 out of our 8 stops.  My friend, still searching for breakfast, got one with a fried egg and brocolli rabe, said it was his favorite of the day.

text:
Tony Luke is tasty! Went around 230 pm in the afternoon on a Saturday. It was busy with a long line. There are indoor seating available which is convenient. Pickles, peppers and ketchup are available. There is even a guy who prepares a pepper trays for you! The cashier is nicer than the cashiers at other famous cheesesteak places in their Philadelphia. 

We ordered Italian cheesesteak and regular cheesesteak with wiz with. The bread is a little different than the other cheesesteak places in philly. The vegetable in Italian cheesesteak is yummy. 

Tony Luke is now on top of my cheesesteak joint list!

text:
As far as Philly goes, this is the place to get your cheesesteak in my humble opinion. I've done Geno's and Pat's and a few others. They're good, but Tony Luke's is the bomb! 

Not only is their cheesesteak the best I've had in the city, but they also boast a few other sandwiches that can be considered the tastiest sandwiches anywhere. Ex. the roast pork, sharp provolone and broccoli rabe. A little bird told me that if you substitute chicken cutlets for the roast pork you will NOT regret it! I eat two cheesesteaks when I come here. It's that good.

Now for the naysayers who act like Tony Luke's is just a tourist attraction and not respected by the hometown crowd. If that's the case why did the Phillies and the Eagles choose to put a Tony Luke's in their stadium? Tony Luke's is doing it big. You can even swing by their location in...Bahrain!

text:
although my current favorite cheesesteak is from John's Roast Pork, trying a cheesesteak from the original Tony Luke's for the first time has made me reconsider them as a second best option.  

Tony Luke's and John's Roast Pork cheesesteaks offers the most quantity of ribeye steak per cheesesteak compared to the other famous cheesesteak joints (Jim's, Pats, Genos, and Delassandros).  the cut of their ribeye steak is tender with no stringy texture, making for an enjoyable experience.  At Tony Luke's, they put minimal seasoning on their cheesesteaks, leaving it up to you as the customer to add however much salt, pepper, ketchup, or hot sauce you desire.  

a big plus is that they do not charge for additional vegetables added to your cheesesteak such as fried onions and mushrooms.  another huge plus compared to the other cheesesteak joints is that they take credit card and not just cash alone! the place is easily accessible with a big parking lot attached as well as ample street parking.  another solid cheesesteak joint in Philly to enjoy if you are nearby!

text: We're in philly for the weekend and did the taste test...we did Pat's, Geno's and Tony Lukes all this morning.  Tony Luke's takes it.
