text:
I've heard of Tony Luke's but hadn't planned on trying them, however my niece-in-law brought us here as she drove us to DC after our stay in Philly. 

ATMOSPHERE:
Covered, open-air lanai seating along a noisy street.  Obnoxiously and incorrectly pronounced customer names over the PA on max volume.  Bathrooms are port-a-potties and there's no where to wash your hands.  Do takeout to enjoy your meal.  

MENU:
Breakfast sandwiches, hot & cold sandwiches, a variety of fries, onion rings, chicken fingers. 

FOOD:
Pork Italian - $9.00
I opted for sharp provolone for an additional $0.50 and chose spinach as my green.  It was good but nothing spectacular.  Soft bread that absorbed the pork juices, overly generous amount of tender and juicy pork slices and sharp cheese that added a nice zing.  The sliced pickles were the perfect accompaniment.  Not as messy a job that I had anticipated. 

SERVICE:
Much is to be desired at yet another Philly establishment that treats you like they're doing you a favor by being there.  On a small positive, it was a much more relaxing experience than ordering at Pat's.

As we sat, a worker in charge of clearing tables also brought over a tray full of condiments from the counter - pickle slices, salt, pepper, chili peppers and ketchup.  A nice touch but a waste of inventory as many things went into the trash. 

When my name was hollered over the PA, I went to the pick up window.  Employee Gina C. asks if I'm Vince.  Yes, I say.  Receipt?  Might have more than one Vince, she says.  As I fetch my receipt from our table, she annoyingly shouts over the PA "HAVE YOUR RECEIPTS READY!?"  Really?  As I'm waiting for my food to be retrieved, I noticed a motivational sign on the wall behind the register stating "Stop being mean to customers!" with pouty emojis.  What a waste of paper its printed on. .  

TIPS:
Have your receipt ready when picking up your food unless you want to be shamed over the PA system. 

Bring handy wipes. 

Thankfully no tipping was necessary even with card payments. 

OVERALL:
Good price and portion, crabby service by Gina C.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
Cheesesteak Wit! Honestly that's all you need to know! When you show up to Tony Luke's you'll see cars everywhere, they have a parking lot but the street will also be lined with cars. And it's no wonder, because the cheese steaks are that good!!

There's seating for about 30 people inside Tony Luke's, and it seems to move pretty quick so it isn't too hard to find a table. Kevin, one of the workers, is an absolute treasure! As soon as a table gets up to leave he's in there making sure it's clean for the next customers. He's friendly and does his job with a smile!

Only tried the cheese steaks and Fries when we came, so I can't comment on the rest of the menu but it is quite extensive. I got my Cheesesteak the most popular way with cheese whiz, and it was a wise decision. I grew up eating cheese whiz in Canada, but never melted, so for me it was a new experience. My husband had his with American cheese and we both agreed wit whiz is the way to go.

Coming in at $9 a piece you can't beat the price for the size. The fries were nothing special, mediocre-at-best I would say but you don't come here for fries anyways.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
I've seen plenty of features about this joint, but never managed to check the place out until recently (which is kind of surprising considering how often I've gone to Philly over the past 20 years).

I showed up and saw the big line and copious sandwich options.  To keep it simple I ordered a steak sandwich with whiz.  It's a solid choice and fortunately this place didn't disappoint.

First off the sandwich is pretty big.  Unless you have a big appetite, you can expect one sandwich to pretty much fill you up.  The meat was pretty awesome and I liked how it was so tender, juicy and perfectly complimented the oozing whiz.  

The folks here got the food out fast and it was great to enjoy the food in all of its grungy Philly glory.  There's no bullshit about their food ... they make great sandwiches and know how to get it done fast!
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
Seriously, this place is such a gem! I've been coming here since I was a little girl and it's only gotten better. My favorite is the chicken cutlet with broccoli rob and extra sharp provolone. Since I'm no longer in the neighborhood, I trek all the way from Northeast Philly. But, man it's worth it! 

I've seen the same employees working here for atleast 20 years, that tells you something doesn't it? The counter staff are always friendly and attentive. Their prices are comparable to other cheese steak joints in Philly, about $9 a sandwich. You can eat inside or take your sandwich to go. There is ample street parking on Oregon ACE.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text: I feel like you have to give this place 5 stars because it is exactly what they say it is- a true Philly samich joint.  That's.  It.  Not the place to go if you're feeling skinny.  There's a wait here like any place that's good.  Pickles on the side.  They have amazingly disgusting and deliciously maple syrup smothered sweet potato fries- you know how I love my veggies.  I was appalled when my bf brought them to the table- I am a salad kind of girl- but... I ate the entire thing.  Try to stop in with enough time before an Eagle's game.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
I once thought Tony Luke's was worthy of being above the "tourist trap" designation. 

It had been a while since I've been here. I gave them a shot today. 

Whatever was not true then may be true now. 

This wasn't a bad cheesesteak. There's nothing wrong with it. But I've had a lot of different cheesesteaks in town since I last had an original Tony Luke. 

And now I'm noticing that the beef flavor just doesn't sit the same way here as other places. I'm noticing that it seems saltier with the cheese. I'm noticing that the flavors don't seem to marry as well as other places. I'm noticing that it seems to be a little greasier than others. 

There's nothing wrong with Tony Luke's. They have many great sandwiches. The rolls are wonderful. 

But as of today, they've fallen out of my top 10 in the city. There's newer places and classic places just doing this sandwich better right now. 

1. Angelo's 
2. John's 
3. Woodrow's 
4. Oh Brother 
5. Dalessandro's 
6. Philip's 
7. Ace of Steaks 
8. Max's 
9. Joe's 
10. Gooey Louie's

Honorable mentions: 
- Jim's 
- Steve's 
- Tony Luke's 
- Ishkabibble's 
- Pat's
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text: Convenient for those coming up and down I95 and hankering for a Philly cheesesteak passing through Philly. Set up is straightforward. Wait on line, make your order, and wait. The waits are a bit long considering the amount of cooks and cookspace in the back. Feel free to partake from the free italian peppers on the side. Hits here are the fries with the works. Natural cut fries cooked perfectly and topped with cheez wiz and bacon bits. Delish. The roast pork with provolone sandwich i found a bit salty but the pork was cooked up great though the broccoli rabe was a bit overcooked. Cheesesteak was satisfying but did not stand out. Great with cheezwiz and the steak was cooked up nicely. All in all i thought everything came across a bit salty. As a destination place though i wouldn't go out of my way but if its in the neighborhood i'll stop in.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
Tony Luke's was my first legitimate cheese steak experience.  I had to have one within hours of touching down into Philly.

Everyone, local and otherwise, suggested Tony Luke's so that's exactly what went on the plan.  I got myself a very easy meat and cheesewhiz only Sammy. No frills. No veggies. No surprises. Just meat and cheese. 

And boy the bread was soft inside, chewy outside, thin sliced meat that quite honestly could have used a bit more salt, and gooey cheezwhiz.

Not bad for my first cheese steak. Let's what the other spots have to offer.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text: The roast pork with the broccoli rabe and steaks are awesome. One of my favorite stops when heading back south.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
I was pleased with the taste of my sandwich. I have only gone to Jim's before. My second time visiting a buddy in Philadelphia. I couldn't come and go without ordering a cheesesteak, but from a different place this time. I'd like to try all the regular spots. I'd rather eat like a local though, not a tourist. 

I was grateful to see all of the positive reviews for Tony Luke's. The prices are not too steep. I ordered a cheesesteak, with sharp provolone. I added sauted vegetables, among them were spinach,  mushrooms, and broccoli rabe. That was exciting too, to add veggies to the mix. It was very tasty and filling. 

The $14 sandwich was longer than my head. I ate about 62% of it, and gave the rest to my friend. He complemented on the taste of the food too. This is a place I would go back to and would recommend lto others, who are new to Philadelphia especially. The customer service was just right, and the crowd was light. The wait wasn't very long, and I didn't feel much intimidation.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text: I think this is the best Philly cheesesteak in Philadelphia. The bread they use is amazing!  Good ratio of whiz to meat so you can taste everything in blissful harmony.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
Once is enough in your lifetime.

and even that maybe too much.

Am I eating the same cheesesteak that everyone else is?

Plain & simple - this isn't philly good.  It's "philly bad".  
  
It was god awful.  The best cheesesteaks are the ones that are chopped up, but the more touristy spots, such as this one, tend to just cook the steakmeat as is.  Fine whatever.  

The meat was so bland that the cheesesteak was lifeless (and this is coming from someone who prefers salt-less food). The meat was tough and chewy - this is top sirloin meat? I don't think so.  They don't use amoroso rolls, but a tougher thicker, slightly more hearty roll.

The fries came in a cute paperbox container - which is fun but the fries were disgusting.  Most of the fries were brown than a crispy yellow.  It has a tough coat and just wasn't yummy.  It was like eating little sticks of brown grease.  The oil either needed to be changed out or they overfried - probably both.

You are better off going to just about anywhere else to get a better cheesesteak. Seriously, anywhere else. 

Don't believe the hype just because it was on Food Network.

There is a station to get your napkins & condiments: ketchup, mustard, pickles. Also, a few bench tables for you to sit and eat there or wait for your order.

Parking - street.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
Quite frankly, I'm sick of eating the cheesesteak, but when out-of-towners come, it is a must (hopefully, my friends don't see this). 

They usually request Pat's or Geno's, but I ignore them bring them somewhere else, like Jim's.

Like all cheesesteak places, the line moves fast. Unlike other cheesesteak places (you, Geno's), they are very friendly. The other great thing is that they have a decent number of tables with a covering overhead (I can't think of a better name at this moment) for cravings on a rainy day.

Personally, I like Jim's better, but I think this is a close second. The pulled pork sandwich was heated the day after, and the bun was not that soggy (but the meat still juicy).

text:
Full Disclosure! I went on a mini cheese steak tour into the city with my friends, and we went to eight total places. My review will reflect my opinion of only a basic cheese steak with choice of cheese, and in comparison to each other. I'll additionally disclose when I went to each place, to consider how full we already were.

Stop 7 of 8. This place was packed, and the food took long. It was tented and had a pretty cozy vibe, but it wasn't clean by any measure. We ordered a cheese steak with onions and American cheese. There was not as much meat but nice ribbons. Plenty of onions and melty American cheese. The favor comes from cheese and a pretty good balance.

text:
Well, fast forward a year or so and my opinion has somewhat changed.  Maybe it's me, but last time I was here, Whiz was an automatic on the cheese steak unless you asked for something else. Of course, I wanted Whiz again so I just ordered my cheese steak thinking that's the way it would come...........WRONG!! Came with American cheese and not much of it to boot.  Hero was underwhelming to say the least. Fries were good as well as the onion rings. Also tried the buffalo chicken pazzotti's which were ok. The highlight of the meal was my sons roast beef with provolone hero. While the roast beef wasn't rare, it was very tender and tasty. Not bad at all. 
        The food wasn't bad at all, but just seemed so much better the last time I was here. That said, everyone here looks like they are miserable!!  From the woman that takes the orders, to the guy that hands them to you, to the guy that cleans the tables!! Everyone had the most miserable expressions on their faces.

text:

Disgruntled cashiers but friendly cooks is something I expected but I didn't expect the dingy port-o-potty's, stench of bleach, sticky tables and a-not-so hygienic sauce bar...these are the only reasons why I'd give this famous location less than stellar review.

text:
****3.5 closer to 4 but I just can't give the  4 stars****


Tony Lukes is a solid Philadelphia experience. Go to the window ask for whatever you see on the menu and don't ask to substitute anything.... They'll give you funny stares. 

First time I came here I got a Philly cheesesteak it's was good, nothing crazy good but a solid cheesesteak. Then I came and tried the chicken cheesesteak, delicious! It's actual chicken breast cut Ito small cubes with American cheese... Nothing else. Nothing else really needed to be in there it was that good. I did add hot sauce to give it a kick. 

There's also a condiment section, hot peppers (not so hot), and pickles, BEST PICKLES EVER!  Tony Luke's is good but I want to try some of the other spots in Philly, this just didn't have that OMG factor.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping

text:
I never had a real cheesesteak in philly, and this definitely felt like the legit spot to get a real cheesesteak in south philly.  What could go wrong?

We arrived and it was very busy, line out the door.  The lady at the register was definitely trying to move briskly through the orders.  I don't really know much about cheesesteaks.  I tried to order a rib eye cheesesteak and roast beef cheesesteak.  As soon as I said roast beef, the lady scoffed at me, that's cold cuts!!!  you want cheesesteak or cold cuts???? so she basically told me not to order something featured prominently on the menu.  uuuuh oookk..... thrown off, I quickly changed to chicken.  Then she said something along the lines of "oh now your changing it up on me". uuuh my bad!!  She could have just let me order what I ordered, or if it's no good take it off the menu?  sorry to hold up your line!!

No biggie.  Another thing, they have huge signs saying something along the lines of we're busy, be sure to check that your order is right (don't remember the exact wording).  Fair enough, and they definitely gave me fries without cheese as I ordered, but I didn't have the nerve to go back and ask for cheese after showing my inaptness at ordering a cheesesteak properly!  

Now to the actual cheesesteaks, they had potential, but just were not that great.  I think I should not have said no to onions, I figured it would be so awesome it didn't matter either way but I was wrong.  There was just not enough flavor with just steak and cheese.  The chicken cheesesteak was not that good either, figures, I guess I wasn't supposed to order that either.  Probably the best thing was the bread, that tasted perfect.

About the cheese, I tried american and provolone, the provolone (i think) was just not enough flavor, the american ok but not great.  I have heard cheese wiz is popular on philly cheesesteaks and my gf said she had it before with the cheese wiz and it was better.  I am just not a big fan of cheese wiz, and couldn't process why I would want cheese out of a can when I can get real cheese.

Overall, still glad I went and tried it.  For me, not friendly to noobs though.  I figured how complicated could it be to order a cheesesteak, I was wrong!  Lesson learned, next time I will know better.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
I took a day trip to Philly in December because I had a cheesesteak craving that just wouldn't go away.  I tried De'Allessandro's last time I was in Philly and it was the best I've ever had.  I decided to try Tony Luke's this time.  The place is located on an industrial-ish looking street and I couldn't really find the parking lot so I parked on the street.  The inside is pretty old and bare bones.  It's pretty crowded and the metal tables aren't comfortable.  The service from the workers I interacted with was pretty 'order your food and get out' status.  However, there was this older black brother working there who asked me if I wanted hot peppers.  I declined, but that was nice of him to ask.  He was also singing like Marvin Gaye as he was going about his work.  I thought that was cool.

I got a cheesesteak ($9.75) with whiz and fried onions and a soda ($2.25).  Total came out to $12.69.  I was kind of disappointed looking at the cheesesteak when it came out because it wasn't nearly as meaty as the one I got from De'Allesandro's.  But the bread they used at Tony Luke's seemed nice.  I also made the choice of getting cheese whiz because I read that is how you're supposed to get it (I got swiss at De'Allesandro's).  I think getting whiz was a mistake though.  It wasn't too bad, but tasted a little too artificial for my liking.  Also they put a little too much of it on the sandwich.  The onions were good.  I have to say there was definitely an addictiveness to the steak at Tony Luke's (maybe all the oil) and it was definitely uniquely satisfying.  

All in all, the cheesesteak was definitely good but it could have been much more meatier and the cheese whiz took away from it a bit.  The price was also OK but not great.  This was a hard decision between 3 or 4 stars but I'm going with 3 cause the experience was a little uncomfortable (what I said about the interior and also factoring in the gruffness from the workers that I interacted with except for Marvin Gaye).  

So in conclusion I'm glad I tried this place.  Food was pretty good but maybe a little overhyped.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text: Duh it's always freaking amazing food! It's the original! What Elise can I say for locals a d visitors is a must eat place for roast pork sandwiches. Cheesesteaks are great too.

name: The Original Tony Lukes

text: Great! Much better than Pat's or Gino's by far!! Unlike Pat's & Gino's they chop up their meat into smaller pieces rather than large slices. Pat's  & Gino's meat is cut way to thick and  you'll  probably choke on it! You'll definitely choke on Gino's because not only is their meat to thick the bread is rock hard! Tony Luke's makes their own bread. Tony Luke's also has a MUCH larger variety than any other cheesesteak provider I've been to in Philly. Many different types of cheese ( pepper jack, American, whiz, horseradish, jalapeo ) and more variety in toppings. The only reason I'm not giving 5 stars is the cheesesteak wasn't greasy enough! That seems to be a common theme with all cheesesteaks I've had, not greasy enough. I want that grease dripping down my arm! If I'm gonna have a cheesesteak I want to go all out! Best cheesesteak I've ever had in Philly was from a food truck on Temple University's campus! Just be warned even when there's a very small line the wait at Tony Luke's is long! Which I won't judge or hold against them because all of their food is fresh and prepared with care. Enjoy!

text: Ordered a cheese steak with wiz, ketchup, salt, and pepper. Bland as anything. The meat had no flavor and they clearly had not seasoned it even though I specifically asked them to. I've had better cheese steaks at the papi store for $5. I can only assume this is another overrated cheesesteak place because it's classic. Brought my steak home and after the first bite I turned on my broiler, opened the steak up and added salt, pepper and muenster cheese, broiled it for about 5 mins and it became edible. The place wasn't even busy and I'm definitely not a cheesesteak snob, I probably have 1 cheesesteak a year and try to go to different places to find a satisfying sandwich. Not sure what was up but I wont be back.

text:
Tony Luke's came so highly recommended, I salivated over the hype well before any griddled and spattered grease clouds taunted the olfactics.

A group of four parked beneath a nearby overpass and left a party of two to mind the wheels while we trekked a slow-paced queue from the front door, through the back corner, to the front corner until finally - the order window.

Being the sandwich that defines a city, downing at least one whiz wit is standard practice. That said, it's impossible to pass up the allure of a roast pork with broccoli rabe and provolone, so my pahdna-in-grime and opted to split the two 'wiches in a battle royale.

In this corner, COW AND PASTEURIZED CHEESE FOOD.
And in this corner, PIG AND PLANT.

dingdingding

Less than four minutes later, the victor emerged, well, victorious. Call it blasphemy, but the cheesesteak didn't hold a candle to the roast pork. Too little whiz over near flavorless, shaved and oil-slicked steak left me bumming, only to be reinvigorated by the sharp provolone, bitter rabe and juicy brined pork. Fantastic bread is a push; the fight goes to PIG.

Like a good anti-tourist, I'll steer clear of the big three in my return trips to Philly and wait in antici... pation for another local CS must-eat. And because there are many, Tony Luke's goes on the back burner.
categories: Sandwiches, Fashion, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Cheesesteaks, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Shopping
name: The Original Tony Lukes

text:
The French Market... a truly wonderful experience. You want thingamabobs, they got at least 20. 

This is a most go for me every time I visit NOLA.  It's an outside shopping area that has so much to see. I definitely would suggest good walking shoes and also go when the weather is nice. The vast majority of it is covered but you have to walk through uncovered streets to get to it.

Cash is another great suggestion, as well as, your camera and an appetite.. as there's a couple food stalls you'll want to hit up. These food stalls include alligator everything, smoothie shops, roasted corn, and an oyster shucker...just to name a few. 

There's trinkets and trumpets, bobbles and bangles galore, and tons of masks. There's used things and new things, hats, local artists, NOLA based photographers, and my favorite the LEGO lady. I can sit there and look at her selection of LEGO characters forever. 

It's a great place to kill an hour or two and get a feeling for the local flare!
categories: Farmers Market, Specialty Food, Shopping Centers, Fruits & Veggies, Fashion, Gift Shops, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Arts & Crafts, Flea Markets, Art Supplies, Food, Flowers & Gifts, Hotels & Travel, Public Markets, Tours, Shopping

text:
Definitely should be a stop as an attraction to visit while in New Orleans! There are various food stops, a flea market in the back, along with art/souvenir type shops in the mix. 

On my trip, we stopped in to check it out and decided to get a classic New Orleans Sno Ball! It is shaved ice with flavored syrup, yum! There are so many flavors. I decided to get the ice cream flavored Sno Ball with condensed milk on top (an extra .50 cents). A small was $3.50 and they only take cash!

text:
This place is awesome. I don't know what all the low ratings are about... it's a flea market. I'm not sure what kind of expectations so many of these yelpers seem to be harboring. I had a blast here, though.

If you wade through enough of the cheaply made mardi gras masks and knock-off "Goach" purses, you can definitely find some hidden gems. I bought a couple of prints from a local artist as well as a unique piece of jewelry from one of the more colorful characters hawking his wares.

I also sampled my first sno-ball here (I never made it out to any of the sno-ball shops *tear*) - a rootbeer flavored sno-ball with condensed milk. OMG. It was so good! And the man who made them was hilarious. After giving me a napkin and a regular sized spoon, he also gave me a sample spoon so I could "share" with my boyfriend. Hee hee!

text:
Perfect place for a NOLA taste. 

Stopped by for a fantastic lunch at NOLA PHO LIFE (separate review, yum). Bought a King Cake (seemingly impossible task come summer time) and then topped it off with a super scrumptious NOLA style sno ball at Mother Nature's Cupboard (Egg Custard, oh my!) Browsed the market's shops between bites and found a few cute NOLA nick-nacks, but nothing that knocked my socks off to the point of purchase. Overall though, a nice little escape from the main street chaos.

name: French Market

text:
There is no doubt this place is very touristic. From the food stands displaying mostly unappealing dishes, to the vendors selling tee shirts, carnival masks, and alligator heads.

Some stands are worth checking out, though. Like the guy selling tiles and magnets depicting authentic ads from the '50s and '60s. Or the semi-antique vendor who had some gorgeous, old 35mm cameras in working conditions. The rest is mainly tacky souvenirs.

Come here not for the shopping, but for the place itself. In the end, this is the oldest public market in the US, having been founded in 1791. What I really liked is the architecture of the market. The black arched metal posts create a nice contrast with the white roof, which also uses a lot of glass, together with some very elegant lights and ceiling fans. I also liked how well the market integrates itself with the surrounding buildings, which also host some interesting artsy vendors. This is certainly a place with its own cultural identity and a certain sense of community.

I took some nice pictures here.

text: We had a lot of fun at the French Market. We started out the trip with a mimosa from one of the first stands. There were lots of food stands with interesting choices, such as sandwiches and fried alligator bites. We had a lot of fun walking through the stands- I bought a New Orleans shirt for my 2-year old nephew, a pair of sunglasses, and a sunglasses case. One of my friends bought some jewelry as well. The stands were diverse, such as photography, clothing, jewelry, and accessories. The French Market wasn't huge compared to markets in other cities, but it was still fun to walk around. Also, the area around the French Market had a lot of shops and places to eat and drink. My only complaint was that when we were finished, we had trouble getting a taxi.

text:
The French Market is one of the best things about New Orleans. The only downside is that one never seems to have enough time to get through it all.

Like most outdoor markets, there are plenty of handmade items, fresh produce, and some kitschy stuff that makes no sense, but here in NOLA, it's that on steroids! You can go on an empty stomach and be able to load up on fresh food, hot and cold, fresh drinks, alco and non-alco, and lots and lots of weird stuff, but also fun decorative items that you would actually be willing to take home. I found a really cool outdoor hanging Fleur-de-lis but there is no way I would be able to get it on the plane so I grabbed a card to buy it and have it shipped to my home. I also scored some handmade candles in cute little jars from Carnival Candle Co. Since I bought those, I have also ordered more to have sent to me since they come in various scents that I adore! 

There is also live music outdoors, street performers, and the Historic Jazz Society is also nesteled into the French Market. 

If you have time, or even if you only have a few minutes, it is totally worth making the top of your NOLA "to do" list!

text:
Half of the French Market was super cool, and the other half not so much.  The super cool half really gives you a sense of what New Orleans is all about...Local artists and cooks are showcasing their specialties.  These items really embody trhe town in that they are locally made and reflect the heritage of the city.  Being a Philly kid, it kind of reminded me of an outdoor Reading Terminal Market.
Then there is an invisible crap dividing line that occurs.  The other side of this division would remind you of a straw market somewhere, where every vendor basically has the same stuff and expect you to negotiate and barter for their goods.  No thanks.
I would highly recommend the French Market for anyone checking out NOLA for the first time, but the latter half isn't worth your time.

text: I love markets. This one was no exception. It was a lot smaller than the ones i've been at in Hong Kong, Aruba, and Panama. The prices were pretty good here. I really enjoyed seeing so many different types of artistry here. There was one guy who made earrings and the paper says "made in the ghetto" which is really unique. There are the very touristy foods such as gator bites, hot sauce store, and oyster bar. There are shot glasses,  Bourbon Street street signs, bracelets made of pennies, Indian shoes, gator teeth on necklaces for $10 each, dresses, and lots of other items. It is worth browsing this area for souvenirs. I got a really yummy po-boy in this area and also looked at a voodoo shop nearby. There is a water view about a block from here!

text:
I love going to markets!  This one was great!  I was looking for souvenirs to bring home that were original to NOLA.  They have a bunch of different things!  Not too far, there's a great flea market with a food court.  Both places had  jewelry, clothes, handmade crafts -- anything and everything, they had!  We walked here...that was probably the only thing that sucked as it was hot and humid.  We ended up taking a cab home.  

My experience at the French and flea market was really nice.  I love coming to places like these and just taking a stroll and looking at everything.  The prices are a little crazy.  They know you're a tourist...but what tourist attraction is cheap, really?  If you liked original pieces from the shops in the French Market, then get it.  Otherwise, if you have the time, shop around or hit up the flea market, ya'll can haggle there.

I recommend visiting both the French and the Flea Market.  It's a nice thing to experience.
categories: Farmers Market, Specialty Food, Shopping Centers, Fruits & Veggies, Fashion, Gift Shops, Used, Vintage & Consignment, Arts & Crafts, Flea Markets, Art Supplies, Food, Flowers & Gifts, Hotels & Travel, Public Markets, Tours, Shopping
name: French Market

text: With the entire French Quarter bursting at the seams with souvenir shops and restaurants, the French Market is still my go-to place for souvenir shopping and to grab a quick bite. Vendors fill their stalls with art, jewelry, masks, t-shirts, hats, keychains and magnets. This is still the cheapest place to grab shirts, masks and magnets from. Some vendors are nice and friendly, some just go through the motions.  Prices are lower than the other souvenir shops, but quality varies as well. If you plan on just picking up some NOLA souvenirs for friends and family, this is the place! The other half of the market have food stalls and "bars". You can grab anything from sandwiches to pralines, to oysters.

text:
Whenever I travel, I always make it a point to visit the local public market if available. I love checking out the unique finds that can't be found in your average souvenir shop. The French Market, unfortunately, didn't quite do it for me.

So the Market is split into two parts, food and gifts. I'll review them separately.

The food section is great! Food stalls are abundant, serving local grub like gumbo, jambalaya, alligator, and oyster. Come hungry and be ready to try a bunch of goodies. There are also shops for you to buy packaged food items to go, like spices, sauces, alligator jerky, and baked goods. But mind you, the prices for these items are higher than you would find outside of the Market. I'm not sure why that is....

The gift section of the Market was a huge disappointment. I was expecting to find unique gifts to bring home, but most of the items for sale were low-quality, made-in-China trinkets I would never want to waste space in my suitcase on. And the kicker is that most of the items weren't even inexpensive! A t-shirt or a necklace will run about $20+ each. Don't waste your money on this; you'll find better gifts for better prices in the cute, small shops on Royal Street.

text:
You definitely want to make the French Market one of your first stops in New Orleans!!!
     You'll find a lot of trinkets and items that are sold throughout the french quarter BUT at a MUCH more affordable price!  Stock up on all you delights that you see before moving on, into the French Quarter. It has a lot of cools stuff, everything from fantastic art, jewelry, mardi gras masks, clothes, and plenty of food stands and market restaurants where you can begin to enjoy all the Cajun/Creole creations from the region! The foods very affordable compared to the French Quarter restaurants, so dig in and get an authentic taste of New Orleans!

text:
Oh man! What discoveries can be made  pied! Had no idea this place was even back of all the party scene! Sorta just stumbled here lol! 
Just like any other outside market with the assortment of vendors, you can buy almost anything here! But be careful of your flight bag! You wouldn't want that to be overweight and cost you much extra to bring all that stuff back that you really don't need in the first place ha!
Me, personally, have scaled down my souvenirs shopping bc I found that most of it collected dust or I started having too many t-shirts lol!
Back to the market!
Yes New Orleans is such a special place, very charming city, beautiful Cajun ppl. 
I'm happy that this was part of our journey on our last day there, topped off a fabulous weekend! This market is located near the Mississippi River, near the streetcars, behind the party scene of Bourbon...
We had a nice stroll, bought a few things, listened to some awesome Creole music, ate some ALLIGATOR and praline beignets! What more can you ask for but a foot massage when you got home lol!
Awesome place! Can't wait to get back!

text:
Just Wow... gigantic sports store...i wasn't expecting it like this from the outside.  It's like Night and day difference once you walk-in.... so much to see and touch and look at...  easily spends several hours here.

I walked up and down left right up and down.  What caught my attention when I walk in was the big Ferris wheel inside.  Only thing close to this I have seen are malls in Hong Kong where they have roller coasters inside.

They even have a Daytona Nascar game with the actual car with actuators and pumps to simulate the real thing... just WOW.

Any person who likes sports outdoors will love this place... AMAZING.

They have all these wild animals with the heads stuff in the gunning area and these fake environmental mountains with dead animals that are real and stuffed...  On top of that they have the famous presidents in wax and when you press a button it talks about some history stuff... i wasn't patient enough to sit through one since there was so much to see.

Everywhere I walk I saw someone holding a bag with Scheels and I wonder what it was.

Overall, amazing store for sport fanatics and outdoors. you'll get an orgasm from this place.  I  heard that their soft serve ice cream is good too.  I need to try that next time.

**parking** 

plenty with the outlet

cash or credit.
categories: Outdoor Gear, Fashion, Men's Clothing, Women's Clothing, Sporting Goods, Gun/Rifle Ranges, Shopping, Active Life

text: This place ROCKS! Wayyyy better than Bass Pro Shops in California! Way better!!!! Not only do they have a huge selection of outdoor/sporting gear etc to choose from, but they have a huge Ferris wheel inside of the mall. It only costs a dollar to ride the Ferris wheel. Along with that, they have several fish tanks throughout the store along with wild life & historical displays. There is also a playhouse for younger kids and a shooting range for the older ones (not a real range, but the one where you shoot the targets in the west). There is a mall on the side of Scheels and several places to eat. It's a great place to visit, get a lot of shopping done & eat! If you haven't been to Scheels yet, you are missing out! text:
My boy was running in the USATF Junior Olympics National Cross Country Championship race.  We are from sunny southern California but here in Reno there was snow on the ground! We had to get spikes or else he would not be able to run without slipping.  We tried several stores in the area but they were all sold out of spiked shoes in his size as well as something called Yaktraks.  So one of the guys who worked at Cabela's told us to give Scheels a try.

We first walked in and it was an amazing store for a sporting goods.  It felt like a large department store but with registers at the front doors like a Target.  So I gotta tell you that yes, they had running shoes with spikes in his size and the Yaktraks.  We got there just in time because it was the last pair of spikes.  Apparently all the coaches were calling and buying products for the snowy race.  One team reserved 90 bags of the actual metal spike bags for themselves.  A young man by the name of Spencer assisted us and did a great job explaining things to us.  He's originally from Iowa and is used to running in the snow.  With his help we picked up a couple more Yaktraks for other team members.  

But what we loved about this store is that it is fun.  They have two large, I'm talking floor to ceiling aquariums filled with live fish swimming around.  You can walk underneath and in between its arches to get a close up view of them.  My kids loved it!  Next they had a full size ferris wheel in the middle of the store!  I thought at first it was just a model but it was actually in operation.  My kids really thought that was neat to ride one inside a store.  My younger boy got his first ride on a ferris wheel at Scheels. And it was only a dollar and for that he not only had a great experience but the guy operating it made it fun.  He has such a good demeanor with the public he was the perfect guy for the job.   

When my older boy went for his ride the first day he saw mannequins on the second floor of U.S. presidents.  So we went up there to view them.  They were on display and you depressed a button and an actor's voice would speak in the president's stead.  They also had a written description of each president's accomplishments.  That was a good idea to put all of this there as it got us to go upstairs.  Now I know that they have large areas for golf, guns, airsoft guns, equipment and hunting clothing.  

After first going that Friday with my older son to get his running shoes/spikes we thought that it was neat that we went back the next day with my younger boy. On that day there was even more fun as they had a live musical marathon where children of various ages were playing classical, holiday and movie theme music on various instruments such as the piano, violin and cellos.  It was very enjoyable as they played so well.  

We also told friends about it.  One of them said that on their way out of town they stopped by to enjoy the store.  That friend said that it was going to probably cost him money because his wife likes to shop and she found some neat things to buy.  

All I've got to say is that we wish we had a Scheels where we live.
categories: Outdoor Gear, Fashion, Men's Clothing, Women's Clothing, Sporting Goods, Gun/Rifle Ranges, Shopping, Active Life
name: Scheels

text:
Awesome place and friendly staff. But they are doing a terrible job with pandemic safety. This is written in August 2021 where masks are enforced by the state of Nevada for all indoor venues. But they aren't enforcing it in their place. They are violating a state mandate. Such a shame considering that this place was 5-stars for me before the pandemic. There are so many fun venues in this huge store and I enjoy it. But their lack of care for COVID safety is what drops this place three stars for me in this time. I don't care about what beliefs or opinions the people running this store have on mask mandates. Safety and public health comes first. 

It's not Scheels' fault that customers are not wearing masks, but if they are not enforcing health regulations and adhering to state mandates, it will be their downfall in the pandemic.

Unless this pandemic completely ends, if you truly care about your safety with COVID, don't shop here. I haven't seen many Yelpers touch upon this issue (given the recent mandates as of this post), so I thought to address it here. They should be enforcing these things in this time.

EDIT: I am giving one star back since the service there id very good. I particularly want to shout out Casey, Cole and Paschence for being very passionate team members that helped me look for stuff. That being said, I'm still very skeptical about covid safety here. But I am giving a little bit more credit where it is due.

text:
Whether your into Sports, Hunting, Fishing, Working out etc, Scheels is your one stop to shop.  Let me tell you all about my experience and my overall thoughts on maybe one of the biggest stores I've ever been in. 

From the time you walk into this store your welcomed by cashiers and then what is my favorite thing in the store is a marvelous looking double arch fish tank now this is the same on either entrance but let me tell you a secret to know what side is to the rest of the shopping center or to the parking lot. Theres two tanks but if you didnt know theres a fresh water/ Salt water fish in one an vice versa. Beautifully made and sometimes you can even see a guy in scuba gear cleaning the units. Pretty awesome! Not to mention Scheels has a Full size Ferris wheel in the center of the Store. Now onto a few areas I liked and that I think needs some improvements. 

** Fishing Area **

Depending on when and what time you go, can vary if you'll have a great time or a bad time. So I mostly go to Scheels cause my wife an I love to fish so every week we go to buy a fishing lure, now when i was looking for a particular looking lure i approached a young and asked "Excuse me, but do you have the Savage Gear Suicide Duck Lure? He then points me into the direction of the hunting equipment, Not! What I was wanting so I was kinda irritated and went to another part of the store an was looking for a manager because I was not pleased with what the young guy an girl were trying to say to me as for what I was looking for "Ducks aren't used in this area for fishing" was what they tried to tell me, the bad thing is I showed them the item on my phone via their website. Manager knew what I had talked about an was able to help me out promptly.

** Sporting gear * Team Apparel **

While looking for my favorite teams from Houston, the Texans, the Rockets an the 2017's World Series Champions the Houston Astros. I first glanced around the store til I was approached by a manager of the area and he asked "Hi, how can I help you" I told him I was looking for gear for my favorite teams so first ones he's like "Texans? Sorry we don't carry them they are out of our district. Rockets? Yeah again out of our district, an so I was kinda like wow! Why am I here. So since it was a few months after the World Series i was thinking maybe some merchandise would be a little lower price and so i asked hey do you have any WS championship merch an he walks me over to the baseball section an shows me 7 racks of LA tshirts an one shirt from the event and i asked any Astro gear, no sorry they are out of the district. I'm stunned and now just bummed out I was turning around an the manager was like "Hey man you can order it online", and without hesitation I then asked "then why have a store??"

Overall my lasting impression of Scheels, if you know what your looking for then your one step farther then you'd get with 75% of the customer service reps standing around the building. I'd like to visit more often but with experiences like these that may not be likely.
categories: Outdoor Gear, Fashion, Men's Clothing, Women's Clothing, Sporting Goods, Gun/Rifle Ranges, Shopping, Active Life

text:
Going Camping? Hunting, perhaps? Fishing? Golfing? Scheels motto is: Gear, Passion, Sports!! It is an astounding 295,000 square feet.

Well you get the general idea. This is a sportsman's or woman's paradise! You will find all sorts of sporting equipment as well as clothing. This is such an amazing store. 

Believe it or not I have come here for field trips. This store is an educators dream as you can shop and educate at the same time. 

Some history: Scheels began as a hardware and general mercantile store in 1902 from a German immigrant who used his first $300 dollars that he earned from his potato farm to open his first store. It is now employee-owned and operated. The store didn't see sporting goods until 1954. 

Between all the sporting equipment on the second floor are 14 animatronic U.S. Presidents that give their famous speeches. The amount of information from the Presidents alone is astounding. Not to mention the huge selection of taxidermy animals usually with information on the animal and genus. Tons of information here. Some of the coolest fish tanks full of fish. 

Your child getting bored with shoppin? Why not take them to the toy Shooting gallery. Reminds me of the shooting gallery at Disneyland in Frontier land. There is a mini bowling  arcade type game too. Did I forget to mention that there is a Ferris Wheel? Yes! A Full size Ferris Wheel! Adults can have fun too at the golf driving simulator. Yes this all cost a small fee to participate in.

Did I mention there is a home decorating area? What if I get hungry? Yep they have that covered too. I have heard that there is a cafe and that the fudge shop has over 30 varieties of fudge.
categories: Outdoor Gear, Fashion, Men's Clothing, Women's Clothing, Sporting Goods, Gun/Rifle Ranges, Shopping, Active Life
name: Scheels

text: We like coming to Scheels for their wide range of selection.  We could literally spend hours here, so we need to be focused if we don't have a lot of time.  Today, we're here to get my bike adjusted.  It sits a little too high and I want more control of it if I am to ride it around town during the Sweet Cycle event.  Scheel's bike department not only sells bikes, but they offer bike service as well.  The adjustment did not quite fix my bike issue, but not for lack of trying from the service people.  They were very accommodating and went out of their way to make it work.  Finally, we decided I may need a new bike (wheeeee!!!) and that's where Bruce comes in.  He is friendly, knowledgeable and had excellent customer service skills.  He assessed my height, my preferences, and what I intend to use the bike for ~ trail riding? NO, street riding? Maybe.  Just ride around the neighborhooh? YES!  He then picked a bike off the rack, and had me test-ride it around the block.  He spoke a lot about technical stuff about the bike, but frankly, I tuned him out.  That's why I brought hubby, so he can pay attention to these things.  I have to say, the bike he picked for me was spot on, and i would've been happy taking that particular one with me.  But he encouraged me to try a different one, for comparison.  He took the time to explain the similarities and the differences between the two and told me to take my time in deciding which one.  He was surprisingly not pushing the sale, which I appreciated.  I would've taken my chosen bike with me, except I didn't like the color.  He encouraged us to shop around and advised us what to look for when shopping at other places.  Very cool.  Overall, we were very pleased with our experience with Bruce.  If it's a toss up between Scheel and somewhere else, or if the difference in price is not significant, I'll gladly bring my business to him at Scheels.  So, if you're in the market for a new bike, or for bike-related services, check out Scheels, and look for Bruce.  He'll take care ya.
categories: Outdoor Gear, Fashion, Men's Clothing, Women's Clothing, Sporting Goods, Gun/Rifle Ranges, Shopping, Active Life
name: Scheels

text:
Wow, this is certainly the Taj Ma-mall.... there's every store you could possibly need in one confined area.  I was working north of Philly last week and was advised by colleagues to go to KoP. I'm not a huge mall/shopping fanatic, so I kinda rolled my eyes. When I was bored last Wednesday night, I decided to drive over to check it out.  At first, I thought it was just an ordinary mall with a few nicer stores. But when you look at the directory, my god, there's every store you can imagine in here :) There are lots of stores & restaurants on the outskirts of the KoP area too, so it's quite easy to get lost in a shopping frenzy.

There is a TON of parking, but once you park, you might do a bit of walking because the buildings are HUGE. I parked in the deck near the Court & walked in to this mayhem of stores- but it wasn't super crowded! I went to Bloomingdale's, West Elm, Urban Outfitters, Macy's, DSW, Nordstrom, and a few other little shops along the way. The mall was very clean, but they need more bathrooms throughout the place. All in all, I'd definitely come back here next time I'm in North Philadelphia :)

text:
This is America's largest mall in terms of square footage at 2.9M SF.  That's even bigger than the infamous Mall of America which is 2.5M SF.  It houses over 400 stores and restaurants on three levels, including seven department store anchors, though one of them is currently vacant.  

MY EXPERIENCE:  
The last time I was here, the mall was oddly located in two separate buildings and quite far from each other.  But, they've recently added a connector wing full of shops to make this mall a single behemoth.   Because the mall is so large, some stores have more than one location.  Maneuvering through the mall can be quite a task as its laid out like city blocks so you'll find yourself circulating the central core along with discovering hidden pockets.  Parking was plentiful but hard to come by due to massive crowds at the time we were there.  Aside from the plethora of shops we browsed through, my stomach is what matters on any vacation, in which it was made happy at The Cheesecake Factory and California Pizza Kitchen. 

HIGHLIGHTS:
- Apple Store
- Bloomingdales 
- Bonefish Grill
- California Pizza Kitchen
- Cheesecake Factory
- Crate & Barrel
- DSW
- Lord & Taylor
- Macy's 
- Maggiano's Little Italy
- Neiman Marcus
- Nordstrom 
- Pottery Barn
- Primark
- Shake Shack
- West Elm
- Yard House

TIP:
A 16-plex theater is located nearby but isn't inside of the actual mall.

OVERALL:
Great variety of tenants, close to the city.

name: King of Prussia

text: First time coming to this mall and it was on black friday weekend. To me this mall seems to have an old and new part to it. There is also a separate mall that is somewhat interconnected through a walkway. The food court in the old part needs to be updated a bit with better lighting and possibly more seating. In my opinion not the  best mall that i have been to, but still decent as it has most of the brand name and luxury stores you want under one roof. BTW this mall has several stores surrounding it like nordstorm rack, best buy, costco, walmart and more so traffic and parking here can be a nightmare

text: A very large mall with a store for everyone and everything. Food stands, sports shops, clothing stores, specialty stores, and more. It's a great mall to see when in the area but not anything unique.

text:
I'm actually quite surprised that such a huge mall can be so very very crowded.  This is a great place to shop if you have the money to do so. We usually just go there when we have a specific purchase in mind - or to window shop. 

It's certainly worth stopping in at least once and other than the Franklin Mills mall, there isn't really a bigger mall (that I've been to) in the area.

name: King of Prussia

text:
Its funny how "special" this place is now...when I was growing up, you would only go here if you wanted to get your car broken into/stolen. 

Just to clarify a misconception...this is in fact the BIGGEST mall in all of America in terms of retail square footage...the Mall of America is bigger overall, but they have tons of other crap that is not retail related. Look it up.

That isn't necessarily a good thing, as the overall infrastructure simply cannot handle the traffic in generates. I dare you to come here during a Saturday afternoon in December...you will want to kill somebody. Linking the Court and Plaza was a great idea, but having it be a street level, outdoor walkway was a stupid idea. "Internal" mall traffic should not interfere with the parking lot traffic, at least, that would make sense to me.

Like any mall nowadays it barely has anything unique or special about it at all...it simply has more of everything. The best part about it is the Rock Bottom brewpub, where you can get some good drinks and pretty decent food and then stumble around the mall and people watch. The latter is a good activity, as you get a neat mix of wannabe sluts, wannabe thugs, country bumpkins, and celebrities. 

The arcade is long gone, the cool record stores are long gone, Toys R Us was still there the last time I checked (as was Bally's...which is still straight outta 1982), and there are a ton of restaurants and other crap that didn't used to be there (and the really old house that was outside by 202 was moved). But, if you want to hang at the "biggest" mall in America, you have nowhere else to go.
categories: Shopping Centers, Fashion, Department Stores, Shopping
name: King of Prussia

text: The biggest mall on the East Coast for sure. You can literally spend all day in this mall. It is a good mall because it has a lot of stores with a variety of everything in there.
categories: Shopping Centers, Fashion, Department Stores, Shopping

text: Simply amazing. This mall has two parts, both of which have an abundance of stores. You can, no you WILL spend your whole day here if you come in the morning. The mall itself is pretty clean and friendly, although very crowded. The food court is very big and pretty good too. This is the best mall in the Philadelphia region, although it's pretty far away. If you are looking to shop at a great mall, the trip here is worth it!

text: My husband and I live in King of Prussia where it is hard to find non-chain restaurants. Blue Pacific is deceiving because it is in the mall, but it is family owned. Their sushi is fantastic and so is the service. We go often with our 1 year old daughter, and she is always welcomed. Great food, highly recommend.

text: Visited this mall over the 4th of July weekend. Man oh man...shopaholics will need some serious discipline and/or a hefty wallet. We got there around 10 when the mall opened so parking wasn't a problem. I really enjoyed perusing through many of my fave stores and was impressed by how large the selections were in many stores compared to regular mall stores. There were also directory assistants around to give directions  and answer questions. Also plenty of good eats in the food courts or surrounding restaurants. Definitely recommend visiting.

text: I did not like this mall one bit. The set up was very odd. I could not figure out how to get to the other half of the mall. I was told we had to exit  out of the main mall to get to the other part of the mall. That just sounds alittle silly to me. The worse part were some of the store employees they were like sweet and sour skittles some were nice and others just  bitter and sour. I can not stand having someone ringing me up and acting as if,  I am invisible. Customer aknowlegement is always nice for example, hello, thank you, bye, thanks for shopping with us.  I felt like I was dealing with zombies here at this mall. Good customer service is hard to find.

text:
Just like every other mall in America, but the nice thing is all the stores you could possibly want are under one roof. Went here on a Monday afternoon during the holiday shopping season and it was not crowded at all- it was nice to shop in peace with only the occasional yelling high schooler here and there. Yes, it's a lot of walking and yes it can get overwhelming or confusing, but I found my way by reading the map just fine, and the mall security guards were very helpful and asked if I needed help while I was looking at the store directory. 

There is a perfect mix of high end and "normal" stores in this mall, which is great if you need to get your shopping done in one shot, versus having to drive to multiple malls. It's also really nice that there is no sales tax on clothes in PA, a luxury I have never had in NYC.

Fun fact, this mall has multiple food courts, and yet doesn't have a McDonald's. Tourists beware, you'll have to make due with "fast casual" establishments such as Melt Shop instead :)

The food court is ok, the food seems very expensive and is just ok. I thought the pizza place was the best, but you can not just order a slice of pizza, you need to get a whole small pizza. 

Great for shopping not for eating.

text: I love this mall, it has everything you could ever want and more. Plus its extremely easy to navigate, and there is ample parking no matter which store you choose to visit. The anchor stores are all substantial in size and offer the best selection in the region when it comes to inventory range and sizes. You definitely can't get through the whole mall in a single day, but if you know what you need or which store you are more likely to find what you are looking for, then you will be just fine!

text:
When I left Philly in 1996, the Plaza had been re-worked and the combined Court and Plaza became the largest mall on the east coast with 300+ stores.

Has it been re-done again?  It looks even more complicated and larger.

I was surprised to see a few stores haven't moved and the food court is still tiny, but the names and faces have mostly changed.

What's great is that anyone can find anything in the two sections of the mall.  None of it's cheap, but when you're at King of Prussia, you can't exactly expect cheap.  It used to be that the Court had the higher end stores, but with Neiman-Marcus and Nordstrom at the Plaza, it's more balanced.

I was surprised that Restoration Hardware and Pottery Barn were separated between the two buildings.  Most places I've been, they're next to each other.

The Philly metro area should be glad to have such a mall.
categories: Shopping Centers, Fashion, Department Stores, Shopping
name: King of Prussia

text:
I really love this mall. It has a huge selection of stores and is fun when I have a whole day to shop.

If you are considering going here, here are some tips and things to think about:

1. Have the whole day to spend to shop, take a break for lunch (California Pizza Kitchen or Cheesecake Factory), and get some coffee at Starbucks.

2. Be in the mood to spend some cash or time to spend scoping out some deals.

3. Be prepared for a lot of people/crowds around. This mall is almost always crowded to some degree.

4. Some stores I always have to check out include: DSW, Urban Outfitters, H&M, Fossil, ALDO, Bloomingdale's, Steve Madden, and Neiman Marcus.

5. If you, like me, do not have an unlimited clothing and shoe budget, be OK with window shopping and enjoying the shopping and fashion experience, without having to buy everything. Going here is sometimes more of an art experience, admiring and appreciating the beautiful fashion at the high-end stores. Some stores I go into I know I probably will not buy anything, but the beautiful clothing is fun to admire or maybe even try on!

I only go here when I have the whole day to shop and a bit of money to spend (does not have to be hundreds of dollars, but enough to have in case I see something really wonderful). And I usually have a shopping buddy to share it with.
categories: Shopping Centers, Fashion, Department Stores, Shopping
name: King of Prussia

text:
I love this mall. Its huge with a wide variety of stores. There's a few reasons I give this mall a 3 star rating. One being the recent attempt of human trafficking. The mall has a very large security staff so why was this man following the 2 teenage girls for 90 minutes without any red flags? Also, the security office has a multi-screened computer system with someone always at the desk, so again why was this man allowed to follow the girls for so long without any confrontation or red flags BEFORE they notified their mother. Another reason for the 3 star rating is the rudeness of patrons. I know the mall can't possibly make everyone be nice but some of the things that I'm classifying as 'rude' are common sense and courtesy. 1) walking in the opposite direction in front of a moving stroller. 2) literally walking so slow in front of a moving stroller and then getting irate when the person pushing the stroller accidentally clips your ankles. (Most of the times it's an accident, I'm a mom myself) 3) when you have the whole hallway to move yourself to where you need to go but you rudely cut yourself in front of a family ordering their Easter bunny pictures. And 4) when you're the last person on the elevator and you see a single parent pushing a stroller towards the elevator, and there's enough room, and you push the 'door close' button. 

I'm sorry but most of these things have made me avoid coming to the mall when schools not in session because 7/10 times its school age kids doing most of these things.
categories: Shopping Centers, Fashion, Department Stores, Shopping
name: King of Prussia

text:
After going to the Home Show at Valley Forge Casino, my wife and I decided to grab some lunch in the KoP Mall.  It's been many years since I've been to this mall, and although the stores are awesome, I think it'll be several years before I come back.

The mall is huge and used to be two separate malls until they built the cover enclosure to make it one massive mall.  There's the high-end section of clothing, handbags, jewelry, watches, the mid-price selection of stores, and a couple of cheaper stores.  There was a hefty handful of "missing" stores.  Some had signage saying something was coming soon, but not all.  You can tell where the better section (newer) food court is, and although nothing is truly dated here, you can tell the older from the newer.  

Be prepared to walk a lot here.  I wish I had my pedometer to see how many miles I logged in this afternoon.  Wife and I mostly had lunch and window-shopped and ended up spending about 3 hours to get through the whole mall.

Have to say that although parking was only a slight hassle, we were lucky to get a good spot near an entrance.  Also felt that the mall did not seem super crowded even with the many thousands in there.

So although I do not have the super-high-end stores near me, mostly everything else the KoP Mall offers I do have a short drive away from home.  The window shopping was a lot of fun at places we can't afford or can't fit in the clothes, but I have no reason to make the special trip just to come here.  We're very fortunate to have what we have near home.  

Staff placed throughout the mall were extremely helpful.
categories: Shopping Centers, Fashion, Department Stores, Shopping
name: King of Prussia

text:
There is a town called King of Prussia, and a MALL inside the town. 

That mall is ingeniously called, King of Prussia Mall.

At the time of this review, this listing is apparently for the MALL, not the town, but Yelp, that's not clear. I asked Yelp to call it, "King of Prussia Mall," and Yelp corrected it for a day, then un-corrected it, so it's back to saying, "King of Prussia," like this is a listing for the town, not the MALL. Whatever.

MALL, MALL, MALL.

This mall is divided into two malls, really, the larger Plaza side (more to the West), and the Court side, east of the Plaza. A covered walkway connects the two if you prefer not to drive around and park from one to another. Just make sure you remember how to get back, because this is an extremely huge property, and you will be walking a very long distance.

KoP claims a location for just about every major retailer in the US, and international companies as well. If the store is not located in the mall proper, it is probably in one of the surrounding shopping centers. One caveat is there is no Dollar Tree anywhere in KoP, nor anywhere nearby. Also, the sole Wawa in KoP is a distance from the mall, almost in Norristown.

Some retailers, like Bath & Body Works, Coach, Pandora, Shake Shack, Starbucks, Sunglass Hut, etc. have duplicate locations, one in each of the Plaza and the Court. Auntie Ann's pretzels has a whopping FIVE locations in the mall! 

KoP is the go-to place to look for a luxury brand in PA (if not in Philly). A good smattering of luxury stores are in KoP, finally a Burberry, then a Gucci arrived a few years ago (just in time for me to have spent $25 to mail an exchange to DC). So the luxe brands are straggling along, arriving fashionably late, I guess. However, if you want Saks, you'll have to go to Bala Cynwyd. Barbour, too, is yonder at Suburban Square (Ardmore). Tod's is nonexistent in the greater Philly area (as their own store). We also have yet to get a Patagonia here in PA (despite FOUR locations in NYC). 

At a time when other US malls are dying out, KoP remains strong. People make this their Friday/Saturday night hangout place, even if just to mill around, and/or go out to eat. Personally, I can't stand the blueish lighting, the clothing starch smells, the dazed people, the obnoxious local teens, etc. enough to do more than get in and out as quickly as possible. But heck, this place is not departing any time soon. The old 80s weekend entertainment is still viable for so many here.

While I don't enjoy hanging out here, I do enjoy this place for its magnitude of retail stores when I need to visit one. I have my parking routine practiced, so I know where to park, depending on what store I need, and I usually pick Nordstrom's lot because it's the easiest in and out ever!

If you're new to the mall, you will probably waste a lot of time figuring out the best route to hit all your stores, and will probably get lost more than once. Also, you should build in a lost 30mins navigating the craziness of all the roads around the mall approach, because it can be confusing just getting into the access roads. And, after all that, on the way home, you may end up headed down 422 instead of the turnpike or something, but you're not alone. Every time I seen an out-of-state plate (even NJ) I get the heck away. I don't want to screw them up, and I don't want to sit behind them as they figure out the behemoth animal that is the KoP Mall! Give yourself a couple trips and you'll have it down. Happy shopping!
categories: Shopping Centers, Fashion, Department Stores, Shopping
name: King of Prussia

This place is ridiculous! I shopped here for my first time this weekend, and it was just about all that I expected it would be. The mall is HUGE! There's a particular section where you enter the particular stores (Gucci, Louie, Prada, etc) and you can basically smell the money in the air.

I think I found one of my new favorite stores: Love Culture. This is the first store of this chain in PA - and in my opinion - it's much better than Forever 21 or any of the other "going-out-clothes" cheaper knock-off girly stores. :) The store is not a mess, and it's bright and full of fashionable bargains.

I hope to have a good excuse to shop at KoP again soon!

text:
I spent some years living in Asia, and I happened to be a couple miles from this REALLY REALLY BIG ASS mall, which I always went to because they literally had everything: food, retail, cinema, bowling, karaoke, bars, amusement park, you name it they had it! I later found out it was the 8th largest mall in the world, which blew my mind mainly because I couldn't believe they could get any bigger.

By comparison, KoP Mall is the 25th largest in the world, which isn't really that big and I didn't get why they had to have a separate building with an uncovered walkway to get there. They even have stores located on the "Outer Perimeter" which you have to drive or walk to. 

There isn't much to do here except shop and dine, and the food options are quite limited especially if you're an avid Yelper and like to avoid typical restaurant chains like the plague. If you love shopping then I guess you're in luck since they have every major and not-so-major retail brands. 

I give this place 2.5 stars.

text:
Where do I start? No, really - that's always how I feel at KoP, and that's usually why I try to avoid it. Nonetheless, I needed to stop by a Pandora store this past weekend, so I headed to this mall, making my boyfriend promise we would be in and out.  

The trip turned out to be a lovely surprise - on Saturday evening (around 5-ish), we managed to find good parking, get to the store, and be helped fairly quickly.  I ended up dragging my guy around when I realized how long it'd been since I'd visited.  We stopped in a couple of stores (including Tesla - how cool!) and the only place that seemed really packed was Starbucks (no surprise there).  While I wouldn't dare go near this place during the holiday season, turns out its not too bad for a regular weekend trip.

text: I came to this mall to check out Restoration Hardware for a couch. I didn't realize that this mall was full of other furniture stores as well. They looked very nice and high-end. Many of them were stores I've never heard of. They had kids play areas and shops like 5 Below, Urban Outfitters, Macy's and Neiman Marcus. I liked that they had a boba tea shop! There is plenty of parking outdoors. The mall is very large and has ample natural lighting. I didn't get a chance to explore the entire mall but the parts that I explored had many home furniture stores that were modern in design. There weren't as many bathrooms as I expected. I had to go through Macy's and go to the third floor to find a women's bathroom. There are a lot of high end stores (i.e. Cartier, Hermes, Longchamp, Burberry) but also more affordable options (i.e. Forever 21, H&M) so I think it's a great mall for all types of shoppers. For entertainment, they have an escape room. For dining, there's fast food options, pretzel stands, tea, donuts, ice cream, and a few sit-down restaurants. I'd love to come back to this mall to explore more!

text:
I used to think that the King of Prussia (KOP) mall was the hottest thing. From a movie theater to numerous restaurants, this mall had everything. Then I moved to Atlanta. I thought I would miss KOP like it's nobody's business. However, I didn't and I still don't.

My first complain would be that It's just too big. I only went to Neiman Marcus or the Plaza area. I never used the other areas of the mall. In fact, I don't even know what's actually out there. I see so many people walking around the mall with a map in their hand. Mall is supposed to be convenient, not "Ugh, where is this store that I'm looking for?"  

Despite its size, I feel like they lack variety when it comes to the stores. Some of the stores are repeated throughout the mall - for instance, there are two Coach stores in the mall, which in my opinion is totally unnecessary. For a mall of this size, you would think there would be Barney's New York or Saks Fifth Avenue, but no. Even Atlanta has them, but not King of Prussia.

Overall, I think KOP is like the gifts you get from your frenemy (Friend-enemy). It has really grand and pretty wrapping, but once you open it, the item is simply useless and awkward.
categories: Shopping Centers, Fashion, Department Stores, Shopping
name: King of Prussia
